Rules.Title: Internal compiler error
Rules.Description: Try to determine whether the compiler is failing because of its inability to parse unexpected syntax. If you receive this error repeatedly, please contact Microsoft.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Internal compiler error - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0001

Rules.Title: Out of memory
Rules.Description: The compiler was unable to allocate enough virtual memory to complete compilation. Close all unnecessary applications and compile again.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Out of memory - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0003

Rules.Title: Warning treated as error
Rules.Description: You compiled with the /warnaserror compiler option, which causes the compiler to generate warnings as errors.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Warning treated as error - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0004

Rules.Title: Compiler option 'compiler_option' must be followed by an argument
Rules.Description: Some compiler options require parameters. If you do not pass the arguments required by the compiler option, CS0005 is generated.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Compiler option 'compiler_option' must be followed by an argument - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0005

Rules.Title: Metadata file 'dll_name' could not be found
Rules.Description: The program was compiled and explicitly passed the name of a file that contained metadata; however, the .dll was not found. For more information, see References (C# Compiler Options).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Metadata file 'dll_name' could not be found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0006

Rules.Title: Unexpected common language runtime initialization error — 'description'
Rules.Description: This error occurs if the runtime could not be loaded. This could occur if the version of the common language runtime that the compiler attempts to load is not present on the machine, or if the common language runtime installation or configuration is corrupt.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected common language runtime initialization error — 'description' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0007

Rules.Title: Unexpected error reading metadata from file 'file' — 'description'
Rules.Description: A DLL was successfully opened for retrieving metadata but is corrupted, such that data could not be read from it. For more information, see References (C# Compiler Options).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error reading metadata from file 'file' — 'description' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0008

Rules.Title: Metadata file 'file' could not be opened — 'description'
Rules.Description: The file specified with the References compiler option does not contain valid metadata.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Metadata file 'file' could not be opened — 'description' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0009

Rules.Title: Unexpected fatal error -- 'error'.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when something completely unexpected occurs to stop compilation.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected fatal error -- 'error'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0010

Rules.Title: The base class or interface 'class' in assembly 'assembly' referenced by type 'type' could not be resolved
Rules.Description: A class that was imported from a file with /reference, is derived from a class or implements an interface that is not found. This can occur if a required DLL is not also included in the compilation with /reference.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The base class or interface 'class' in assembly 'assembly' referenced by type 'type' could not be resolved - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0011

Rules.Title: The type 'type' is defined in an assembly that is not referenced. You must add a reference to assembly 'assembly'.
Rules.Description: The definition for a referenced type was not found. This could occur if a required .DLL file is not included in the compilation. For more information, see Add Reference Dialog Box and References (C# Compiler Options).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type 'type' is defined in an assembly that is not referenced. You must add a reference to assembly 'assembly'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0012

Rules.Title: Unexpected error writing metadata to file 'ModelStore.dll' -- 'No logical space left to create more user strings.
Rules.Description: The .NET runtime did not emit metadata. Check to make sure that the path is correct and that the disk is not full. If the problem persists, you may have to repair or reinstall Visual Studio and/or .NET.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error writing metadata to file 'ModelStore.dll' -- 'No logical space left to create more user strings. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0013

Rules.Title: Required file 'file' could not be found
Rules.Description: A file is needed by the compiler but is not on the system. Make sure that the path is correct. If the file is a Visual Studio system file, then you may need to repair your installation or else remove and reinstall Visual Studio completely.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Required file 'file' could not be found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0014

Rules.Title: The name of type 'type' is too long
Rules.Description: The fully qualified name of a user-defined type must have fewer than 1024 characters, including the periods.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The name of type 'type' is too long - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0015

Rules.Title: Could not write to output file 'file' — 'reason'
Rules.Description: The compiler could not write to an output file. Check the path to the file to make sure it exists. If a previously built file is already at the location, make sure it is writeable, and that no process currently has a lock on the file. For example, make sure your executable is not running when you attempt to build.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Could not write to output file 'file' — 'reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0016

Rules.Title: Program 'output file name' has more than one entry point defined. Compile with /main to specify the type that contains the entry point.
Rules.Description: A program can only have one Main method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Program 'output file name' has more than one entry point defined. Compile with /main to specify the type that contains the entry point. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0017

Rules.Title: Operator 'operator' cannot be applied to operands of type 'type' and 'type'
Rules.Description: A binary operator is applied to data types that do not support it. For example, you cannot use the || operator on strings, you cannot use +, -, <, or > operators on bool variables, and you cannot use the == operator with a struct type unless the type explicitly overloads that operator.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Operator 'operator' cannot be applied to operands of type 'type' and 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0019

Rules.Title: Division by constant zero
Rules.Description: An expression uses a literal (not variable) value of zero in the denominator of a division operation. Division by zero is not defined, and is therefore invalid.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Division by constant zero - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0020

Rules.Title: Cannot apply indexing with [] to an expression of type 'type'
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to access a value through an indexer on a data type that does not support Indexers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot apply indexing with [] to an expression of type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0021

Rules.Title: Wrong number of indices inside [], expected 'number'
Rules.Description: An array-access operation specified the incorrect number of dimensions within the square brackets. For more information, see Arrays.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Wrong number of indices inside [], expected 'number' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0022

Rules.Title: Operator 'operator' cannot be applied to operand of type 'type'
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to apply an operator to a variable whose type was not designed to work with the operator. For more information, see Types and C# Operators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Operator 'operator' cannot be applied to operand of type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0023

Rules.Title: Standard library file 'file' could not be found
Rules.Description: A file that is needed by the compiler was not found. Check that the path is correct and that the file exists.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Standard library file 'file' could not be found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0025

Rules.Title: Keyword 'this' is not valid in a static property, static method, or static field initializer
Rules.Description: The this keyword refers to an object, which is an instance of a type. Since static methods are independent of any instance of the containing class, the "this" keyword is meaningless and is therefore not allowed. For more information, see Static Classes and Static Class Members and Objects.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Keyword 'this' is not valid in a static property, static method, or static field initializer - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0026

Rules.Title: Keyword 'this' is not available in the current context
Rules.Description: The this keyword was found outside of a property, method, or constructor.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Keyword 'this' is not available in the current context - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0027

Rules.Title: Cannot implicitly convert type 'type' to 'type'
Rules.Description: The compiler requires an explicit conversion. For example, you may need to cast an r-value to be the same type as an l-value. Or, you must provide conversion routines to support certain operator overloads.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot implicitly convert type 'type' to 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0029

Rules.Title: Cannot convert type 'type' to 'type'
Rules.Description: There is no predefined conversion between types. You can define a custom conversion between those types. For more information, see User-defined conversion operators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert type 'type' to 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0030

Rules.Title: Constant value 'value' cannot be converted to a 'type'.
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to assign a value to a variable whose type cannot store the value. For more information, see Types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Constant value 'value' cannot be converted to a 'type'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0031

Rules.Title: Operator 'operator' is ambiguous on operands of type 'type1' and 'type2'
Rules.Description: An operator was used on two objects and the compiler found more than one conversion. Because conversions have to be unique, you either have to make a cast or to make one of the conversions explicit. For more information, see User-defined conversion operators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Operator 'operator' is ambiguous on operands of type 'type1' and 'type2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0034

Rules.Title: Operator 'operator' is ambiguous on an operand of type 'type'
Rules.Description: The compiler has more than one available conversion and does not know which to choose before applying the operator.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Operator 'operator' is ambiguous on an operand of type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0035

Rules.Title: An out parameter cannot have the '[In]' attribute
Rules.Description: Currently, the In attribute is not permitted on an out parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An out parameter cannot have the '[In]' attribute - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0036

Rules.Title: Cannot convert null to 'type' because it is a non-nullable value type
Rules.Description: The compiler cannot assign null to a value type; null can only be assigned to a reference type or to a nullable value type. struct is a value type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert null to 'type' because it is a non-nullable value type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0037

Rules.Title: Cannot access a nonstatic member of outer type 'type1' via nested type 'type2'
Rules.Description: A field in a class is not automatically available to a nested class. To be available to a nested class, the field must be static. Otherwise, you must create an instance of the outer class. For more information, see Nested Types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot access a nonstatic member of outer type 'type1' via nested type 'type2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0038

Rules.Title: Cannot convert type 'type1' to 'type2' via a reference conversion, boxing conversion, unboxing conversion, wrapping conversion, or null type conversion
Rules.Description: A conversion with the as operator is allowed by inheritance, reference conversions, and boxing conversions.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert type 'type1' to 'type2' via a reference conversion, boxing conversion, unboxing conversion, wrapping conversion, or null type conversion - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0039

Rules.Title: Unexpected error creating debug information file — 'reason'
Rules.Description: This error can occur when using the DebugType compiler option and indicates that the compiler was unable to write to the .pdb file. Possible resolutions to this error include reinstalling Visual Studio, ensuring that the compiler has write access to a file or directory, or not compiling with /debug.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error creating debug information file — 'reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0040

Rules.Title: Unexpected error writing debug information -- '{error}'
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error writing debug information -- '{error}' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0041

Rules.Title: Unexpected error creating debug information file 'file' — 'reason'
Rules.Description: The compiler could not create the debug information; reason contains additional information on the error condition.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error creating debug information file 'file' — 'reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0042

Rules.Title: PDB file 'file' has an incorrect or out-of-date format. Delete it and rebuild.
Rules.Description: Delete the .pdb file for this compilation and recompile.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - PDB file 'file' has an incorrect or out-of-date format. Delete it and rebuild. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0043

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than method 'method'
Rules.Description: The return type and each of the types referenced in the formal parameter list of a method must be at least as accessible as the method itself. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than method 'method' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0050

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than method 'method'
Rules.Description: The return type and each of the types referenced in the formal parameter list of a method must be at least as accessible as the method itself. Make sure the types used in method signatures are not accidentally private due to the omission of the public modifier. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than method 'method' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0051

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: field type 'type' is less accessible than field 'field'
Rules.Description: The type of a field cannot be less accessible than the field itself because all public constructs must return a publicly accessible object.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: field type 'type' is less accessible than field 'field' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0052

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: property type 'type' is less accessible than property 'property'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: property type 'type' is less accessible than property 'property' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0053

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: indexer return type 'type' is less accessible than indexer 'indexer'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: indexer return type 'type' is less accessible than indexer 'indexer' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0054

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than indexer 'indexer'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than indexer 'indexer' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0055

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than operator 'operator'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than operator 'operator' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0056

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than operator 'operator'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than operator 'operator' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0057

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than delegate 'delegate'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: return type 'type' is less accessible than delegate 'delegate' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0058

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than delegate 'delegate'
Rules.Description: The return type and each of the types referenced in the formal parameter list of a method must be at least as accessible as the method itself. For more information, see Access Modifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: parameter type 'type' is less accessible than delegate 'delegate' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0059

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: base class 'class1' is less accessible than class 'class2'
Rules.Description: Class accessibility should be consistent between the base class and inherited class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: base class 'class1' is less accessible than class 'class2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0060

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: base interface 'interface 1' is less accessible than interface 'interface 2'
Rules.Description: A public construct must return a publicly accessible object.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: base interface 'interface 1' is less accessible than interface 'interface 2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0061

Rules.Title: 'event' : event property must have both add and remove accessors
Rules.Description: An event that is not a field must have both access methods.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'event' : event property must have both add and remove accessors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0065

Rules.Title: 'event': event must be of a delegate type
Rules.Description: The event keyword requires a delegate type. For more information, see Events and Delegates.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'event': event must be of a delegate type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0066

Rules.Title: 'event': event in interface cannot have initializer
Rules.Description: An event in an interface cannot have an initializer. For more information, see Interfaces.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'event': event in interface cannot have initializer - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0068

Rules.Title: An event in an interface cannot have add or remove accessors
Rules.Description: You cannot define an event's accessor functions in an interface. For more information, see Events and Interfaces.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An event in an interface cannot have add or remove accessors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0069

Rules.Title: The event 'event' can only appear on the left hand side of += or -= (except when used from within the type 'type')
Rules.Description: Outside of the class it is defined in, an event can only add or subtract references. For more information, see Events.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The event 'event' can only appear on the left hand side of += or -= (except when used from within the type 'type') - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0070

Rules.Title: An explicit interface implementation of an event must use event accessor syntax
Rules.Description: When explicitly implementing an event that was declared in an interface, you must manually provide the add and remove event accessors that are typically provided by the compiler. The accessor code can connect the interface event to another event in your class (shown later in this topic) or to its own delegate type. For more information, see How to implement interface events.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An explicit interface implementation of an event must use event accessor syntax - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0071

Rules.Title: 'event' : cannot override; 'method' is not an event
Rules.Description: An event can only override another event. For more information, see Events.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'event' : cannot override; 'method' is not an event - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0072

Rules.Title: An add or remove accessor must have a body
Rules.Description: An add or remove keyword in an event definition must have a body. For more information, see Events.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An add or remove accessor must have a body - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0073

Rules.Title: 'event': abstract event cannot have initializer
Rules.Description: If an event is marked as abstract, it cannot be initialized. For more information, see Events.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'event': abstract event cannot have initializer - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0074

Rules.Title: To cast a negative value, you must enclose the value in parentheses
Rules.Description: If you are casting using a keyword that identifies a predefined type, then you do not need parentheses. Otherwise, you must put the parentheses because (x) –y will not be considered a cast expression. From the C# Specification, Section 7.6.6:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - To cast a negative value, you must enclose the value in parentheses - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0075

Rules.Title: The enumerator name 'value__' is reserved and cannot be used
Rules.Description: An item in an enumeration cannot have an identifier called value__.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The enumerator name 'value__' is reserved and cannot be used - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0076

Rules.Title: The as operator must be used with a reference type or nullable type ('int' is a non-nullable value type).
Rules.Description: The as operator was passed a value type. Because as can return null, it can only be passed a reference type or a nullable value type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The as operator must be used with a reference type or nullable type ('int' is a non-nullable value type). - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0077

Rules.Title: The event 'event' can only appear on the left hand side of += or -=
Rules.Description: An event was called incorrectly. For more information, see Events and Delegates.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The event 'event' can only appear on the left hand side of += or -= - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0079

Rules.Title: Constraints are not allowed on non-generic declarations
Rules.Description: The syntax found may only be used in a generic declaration to apply constraints to the type parameter. For more information, see Generics.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Constraints are not allowed on non-generic declarations - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0080

Rules.Title: Type parameter declaration must be an identifier not a type
Rules.Description: When you declare a generic method or type, specify the type parameter as an identifier, for example "T" or "inputType". When client code calls the method, it supplies the type, which replaces each occurrence of the identifier in the method or class body. For more information, see Generic Type Parameters.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type parameter declaration must be an identifier not a type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0081

Rules.Title: Type 'type' already reserves a member called 'name' with the same parameter types
Rules.Description: Properties at compile time are translated to methods with get_ and/or set_ in front of the identifier. If you define your own method that conflicts with the method name, an error is generated.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type 'type' already reserves a member called 'name' with the same parameter types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0082

Rules.Title: The parameter name 'parameter name' is a duplicate
Rules.Description: A method declaration used the same parameter name more than once. Parameter names must be unique in a method declaration. For more information, see Methods.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The parameter name 'parameter name' is a duplicate - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0100

Rules.Title: The namespace 'namespace' already contains a definition for 'type'
Rules.Description: A namespace has duplicate identifiers. Rename or delete one of the duplicate identifiers. For more information, see Namespaces
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The namespace 'namespace' already contains a definition for 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0101

Rules.Title: The type 'type name' already contains a definition for 'identifier'
Rules.Description: A class contains multiple declarations for identifiers with the same name at the same scope. To fix the error, rename the duplicate identifiers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type 'type name' already contains a definition for 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0102

Rules.Title: The name 'identifier' does not exist in the current context
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to use a name that does not exist in the class, namespace, or scope. Check the spelling of the name and check your using directives and assembly references to make sure that the name that you are trying to use is available.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The name 'identifier' does not exist in the current context - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0103

Rules.Title: 'reference' is an ambiguous reference between 'identifier' and 'identifier'
Rules.Description: Your program contains using directives for two namespaces and your code references a name that appears in both namespaces.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'reference' is an ambiguous reference between 'identifier' and 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0104

Rules.Title: The modifier 'modifier' is not valid for this item
Rules.Description: A class or interface member was marked with an invalid access modifier. The following examples describe some of these invalid modifiers:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The modifier 'modifier' is not valid for this item - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0106

Rules.Title: More than one protection modifier
Rules.Description: Only one access modifier (public, private, protected, or internal) is allowed on a class member, with the exception of protected internal and private protected.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - More than one protection modifier - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0107

Rules.Title: The evaluation of the constant value for 'const declaration' involves a circular definition
Rules.Description: The declaration of a const variable (a) cannot reference another const variable (b) that also references (a).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The evaluation of the constant value for 'const declaration' involves a circular definition - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0110

Rules.Title: Type 'class' already defines a member called 'member' with the same parameter types
Rules.Description: CS0111 occurs if a class contains two member declarations with the same name and parameter types. For more information, see Methods.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type 'class' already defines a member called 'member' with the same parameter types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0111

Rules.Title: A static member 'function' cannot be marked as override, virtual or abstract
Rules.Description: Any method declaration that uses the override, virtual, or abstract keyword cannot also use the static keyword.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A static member 'function' cannot be marked as override, virtual or abstract - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0112

Rules.Title: A member 'function' marked as override cannot be marked as new or virtual
Rules.Description: It is mutually exclusive to mark a method with the new and override keywords.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A member 'function' marked as override cannot be marked as new or virtual - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0113

Rules.Title: 'function' : no suitable method found to override
Rules.Description: A method was marked as an override, but the compiler found no method to override. For more information, see override, and Knowing When to Use Override and New Keywords.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'function' : no suitable method found to override - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0115

Rules.Title: A namespace cannot directly contain members such as fields or methods.
Rules.Description: A namespace can contain other namespaces, structs, and classes. For more information, see the namespace keyword article.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A namespace cannot directly contain members such as fields or methods. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0116

For more information about how types are determined, see Conditional operator cannot cast implicitly.

Rules.TitleAndLink: - The class type constraint 'constraint' must come before any other constraints - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0406

Rules.Title: 'return-type method' has the wrong return type
Rules.Description: The method was not compatible with the delegate type. The argument types matched, but the return type was not the correct return type for that delegate. To avoid this error, use a different method, change the method's return type, or change the delegate's return type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'return-type method' has the wrong return type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0407

Rules.Title: A constraint clause has already been specified for type parameter 'type parameter'. All of the constraints for a type parameter must be specified in a single where clause.
Rules.Description: Multiple constraint clauses (where clauses) were found for a single type parameter. Remove the extraneous where clause, or correct the where clauses so that a unique type parameter in each clause.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A constraint clause has already been specified for type parameter 'type parameter'. All of the constraints for a type parameter must be specified in a single where clause. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0409

Rules.Title: No overload for 'method' has the correct parameter and return types
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you try to instantiate a delegate with a function that has the wrong parameter types. The parameter types of the delegate must match the function that you are assigning to the delegate.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - No overload for 'method' has the correct parameter and return types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0410

Rules.Title: The type arguments for method 'method' cannot be inferred from the usage. Try specifying the type arguments explicitly.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you call a generic method without explicitly providing the type arguments and the compiler cannot infer which type arguments are intended. To avoid this error, add the intended type arguments in angle brackets.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type arguments for method 'method' cannot be inferred from the usage. Try specifying the type arguments explicitly. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0411

Rules.Title: 'generic': a parameter or local variable cannot have the same name as a method type parameter
Rules.Description: There is a name conflict between the type parameter of a generic method and a local variable in the method or one of the method's parameters. To avoid this error, rename any conflicting parameters or local variables.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'generic': a parameter or local variable cannot have the same name as a method type parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0412

Rules.Title: The type parameter 'type parameter' cannot be used with the 'as' operator because it does not have a class type constraint nor a 'class' constraint
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a generic type uses the as operator, but that generic type does not have a class type constraint. The as operator is only allowed with reference and nullable value types, so the type parameter must be constrained to guarantee that it is not a value type. To avoid this error, use a class type constraint or a reference type constraint.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type parameter 'type parameter' cannot be used with the 'as' operator because it does not have a class type constraint nor a 'class' constraint - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0413

Rules.Title: The 'IndexerName' attribute is valid only on an indexer that is not an explicit interface member declaration
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you use an IndexerName attribute on an indexer that was an explicit implementation of an interface. This error may be avoided by removing the interface name from the declaration of the indexer, if possible. For more information, see the IndexerNameAttribute Class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The 'IndexerName' attribute is valid only on an indexer that is not an explicit interface member declaration - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0415

Rules.Title: 'type parameter': an attribute argument cannot use type parameters
Rules.Description: A type parameter was used as an attribute argument, which is not allowed. Use a non-generic type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type parameter': an attribute argument cannot use type parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0416

Rules.Title: 'identifier': cannot provide arguments when creating an instance of a variable type
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a call to the new operator on a type parameter has arguments. The only constructor that can be called by using the new operator on an unknown parameter type is a constructor that has no arguments. If you need to call another constructor, consider using a class type constraint or interface constraint.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'identifier': cannot provide arguments when creating an instance of a variable type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0417

Rules.Title: 'class name': an abstract class cannot be sealed or static
Rules.Description: An abstract class cannot be used to create objects unless it is derived from, so it makes no sense to be sealed. An abstract class cannot meaningfully be static either; abstract classes are designed to support an object hierarchy that will use the abstract class as a base.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class name': an abstract class cannot be sealed or static - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0418

Rules.Title: Since 'class' has the ComImport attribute, 'method' must be extern or abstract
Rules.Description: Specifying the ComImport attribute implies that the implementation for the class is to be imported from a COM module. Additional methods may not be defined.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Since 'class' has the ComImport attribute, 'method' must be extern or abstract - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0423

Rules.Title: 'class': a class with the ComImport attribute cannot specify a base class
Rules.Description: Specifying the ComImportAttribute attribute implies that the implementation for the class is to be imported from a COM module. Additional methods or fields inherited from the base class are not allowed to be added to the implementation defined in the COM module.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class': a class with the ComImport attribute cannot specify a base class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0424

Rules.Title: The constraints for type parameter 'type parameter' of method 'method' must match the constraints for type parameter 'type parameter' of interface method 'method'. Consider using an explicit interface implementation instead.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a virtual generic method is overridden in a derived class and the constraints on the method in the derived class do not match the constraints on the method in the base class. To avoid this error, make sure the where clause is identical in both declarations, or implement the interface explicitly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The constraints for type parameter 'type parameter' of method 'method' must match the constraints for type parameter 'type parameter' of interface method 'method'. Consider using an explicit interface implementation instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0425

Rules.Title: The type name 'identifier' does not exist in the type 'type'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you reference a type nested within another type, but no such nested type exists. This can occur if you mistype the name of the nested type. Check the spelling of the names used, and verify that the enclosing type has the expected member.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type name 'identifier' does not exist in the type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0426

Rules.Title: Cannot convert method group 'Identifier' to non-delegate type 'type'.  Did you  intend to invoke the method?
Rules.Description: This error occurs when converting a method group to a non-delegate type, or attempting to invoke a method without using parentheses.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert method group 'Identifier' to non-delegate type 'type'.  Did you  intend to invoke the method? - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0428

Rules.Title: The extern alias 'alias' was not specified in a /reference option
Rules.Description: This error occurs when extern Alias is encountered but Alias was not specified as a reference on the command line. To resolve CS0430, compile with /reference.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The extern alias 'alias' was not specified in a /reference option - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0430

Rules.Title: Cannot use alias 'identifier' with '::' since the alias references a type. Use '.' instead.
Rules.Description: You used "::" with an alias that references a type. To resolve this error, use the "." operator.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use alias 'identifier' with '::' since the alias references a type. Use '.' instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0431

Rules.Title: Alias 'identifier' not found
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you use "::" to the right of an identifier that is not an alias. To resolve the error, use "." instead.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Alias 'identifier' not found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0432

Rules.Title: The type TypeName1 exists in both TypeName2 and TypeName3
Rules.Description: Two different assemblies referenced in your application contain the same namespace and type, which produces ambiguity.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type TypeName1 exists in both TypeName2 and TypeName3 - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0433

Rules.Title: The namespace NamespaceName1 in NamespaceName2 conflicts with the type TypeName1 in NamespaceName3
Rules.Description: This error occurs when an imported type and an imported nested namespace have the same fully qualified name. When that name is referenced, the compiler is unable to distinguish between the two. If you can change the imported source code, you can resolve the error by changing the name of either the type or the namespace so that both are unique within the assembly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The namespace NamespaceName1 in NamespaceName2 conflicts with the type TypeName1 in NamespaceName3 - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0434

Rules.Title: The type 'type' in 'module_1' conflicts with the namespace 'namespace' in 'module_2'.
Rules.Description: This error occurs when a type in a source file conflicts with a namespace in another source file. This typically happens when one or both come from an added module. To resolve, rename the type or the namespace that caused the conflict.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type 'type' in 'module_1' conflicts with the namespace 'namespace' in 'module_2'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0438

Rules.Title: An extern alias declaration must precede all other elements defined in the namespace
Rules.Description: This error occurs when an extern declaration comes after something else, such as a using declaration, in the same namespace. The extern declarations must come before all other namespace elements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An extern alias declaration must precede all other elements defined in the namespace - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0439

Rules.Title: 'class': a class cannot be both static and sealed
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you declare a class that is both static and sealed. Static classes are inherently sealed, so the sealed modifier is not necessary. To resolve, use one modifier only.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class': a class cannot be both static and sealed - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0441

Rules.Title: 'Property': abstract properties cannot have private accessors
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you use the access modifier "private" to modify an abstract accessor. To resolve, use a different access modifier, or make the property non-abstract.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Property': abstract properties cannot have private accessors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0442

Rules.Title: Syntax error, value expected
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you reference an array without specifying a value for the array index.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Syntax error, value expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0443

Rules.Title: Cannot modify the result of an unboxing conversion
Rules.Description: The result of an unboxing conversion is a temporary variable. The compiler prevents you from modifying such variables because any modification would go away when the temporary variable goes away. To fix this, declare a new value-type variable to store the intermediate expression, and assign the result of the unboxing conversion to that variable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot modify the result of an unboxing conversion - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0445

Rules.Title: Foreach cannot operate on a 'Method or Delegate'. Did you intend to invoke the 'Method or Delegate'?
Rules.Description: This error is caused by specifying a method without parentheses or an anonymous method without parentheses in the part of the foreach statement where you would normally put a collection class. Note that it is valid, though unusual, to put a method call in that location, if the method returns a collection class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Foreach cannot operate on a 'Method or Delegate'. Did you intend to invoke the 'Method or Delegate'? - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0446

Rules.Title: Attributes cannot be used on type arguments, only on type parameters
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you apply an attribute to a type argument that occurs in an invocation statement. It is acceptable to apply an attribute to a type parameter in a class or method declaration statement such as the following:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Attributes cannot be used on type arguments, only on type parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0447

Rules.Title: The return type for ++ or -- operator must be the containing type or derived from the containing type
Rules.Description: When you override the ++ or -- operators, they must return the same type as the containing type, or return a type that is derived from the containing type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The return type for ++ or -- operator must be the containing type or derived from the containing type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0448

Rules.Title: The 'class' or 'struct' constraint must come before any other constraints
Rules.Description: The constraints on the type parameter of a generic type or method must occur in a specific order: class or struct must be first, if present, then any interface constraints, and finally any constructor constraints. This error is caused by the class or struct constraint not appearing first. To resolve this error, reorder the constraint clauses.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The 'class' or 'struct' constraint must come before any other constraints - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0449

Rules.Title: 'Type Parameter Name': cannot specify both a constraint class and the 'class' or 'struct' constraint
Rules.Description: If a type parameter is constrained by the struct type constraint, it is logically contradictory for it to also be constrained by a specific class type, since struct and class are mutually exclusive categories. If a type parameter is constrained by a specific class type constraint, then it is by definition constrained by the class type constraint, and so specifying the class type constraint is redundant.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Type Parameter Name': cannot specify both a constraint class and the 'class' or 'struct' constraint - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0450

Rules.Title: The 'new()' constraint cannot be used with the 'struct' constraint
Rules.Description: When specifying constraints on the type of a generic, the new() constraint may only be used with class type constraints, interface type constraints, reference type constraints, and type parameter constraints, but not with value type constraints.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The 'new()' constraint cannot be used with the 'struct' constraint - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0451

Rules.Title: The type 'type name' must be a reference type in order to use it as parameter 'parameter name' in the generic type or method 'identifier of generic'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you pass a value type such as a struct or int as a parameter to a generic type or method that has a reference type constraint.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type 'type name' must be a reference type in order to use it as parameter 'parameter name' in the generic type or method 'identifier of generic' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0452

Rules.Title: The type 'Type Name' must be a non-nullable value type in order to use it as parameter 'Parameter Name' in the generic type or method 'Generic Identifier'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you use a non-value type argument in instantiating a generic type or method that has the value constraint on it. It can also occur when you use a nullable value type argument. See the last two lines of code in the following example.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type 'Type Name' must be a non-nullable value type in order to use it as parameter 'Parameter Name' in the generic type or method 'Generic Identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0453

Rules.Title: Circular constraint dependency involving 'Type Parameter 1' and 'Type Parameter 2'
Rules.Description: This error arises because at some point one type parameter refers to another, and the second refers back to the first. To fix this error, break the circular dependency by removing one of the constraints. Note that the circular constraint dependency can be indirect.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Circular constraint dependency involving 'Type Parameter 1' and 'Type Parameter 2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0454

Rules.Title: Type parameter 'Type Parameter Name' inherits conflicting constraints 'Constraint Name 1' and 'Constraint Name 2'
Rules.Description: Two common ways to get this error are to set up constraints so that the type parameter derives from two non-related classes, or so that it derives from a class type or reference type constraint and a struct type or value type constraint. To resolve this error, remove the conflict from your inheritance hierarchy.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type parameter 'Type Parameter Name' inherits conflicting constraints 'Constraint Name 1' and 'Constraint Name 2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0455

Rules.Title: Type parameter 'Type Parameter Name 1' has the 'struct' constraint so 'Type Parameter Name 1' cannot be used as a constraint for 'Type Parameter Name 2'
Rules.Description: Value type constraints are implicitly sealed so those constraints cannot be used as constraints on a second type parameter. This is because value types cannot be overridden. To resolve this error, put a value type constraint directly on the second type parameter, instead of doing so indirectly by means of the first type parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type parameter 'Type Parameter Name 1' has the 'struct' constraint so 'Type Parameter Name 1' cannot be used as a constraint for 'Type Parameter Name 2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0456

Rules.Title: Ambiguous user defined conversions 'Conversion method name 1' and 'Conversion method name 2' when converting from 'type name 1' to 'type name 2'
Rules.Description: Two conversion methods are applicable, and the compiler is unable to decide which one to use.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Ambiguous user defined conversions 'Conversion method name 1' and 'Conversion method name 2' when converting from 'type name 1' to 'type name 2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0457

Rules.Title: Cannot take the address of a read-only local variable
Rules.Description: There are three common scenarios in the C# language that generate read-only local variables: foreach, using, and fixed. In each of these cases, you are not allowed to write to the read-only local variable, or to take its address. This error is generated when the compiler realizes you are trying to take the address of a read-only local variable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot take the address of a read-only local variable - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0459

Rules.Title: Constraints for override and explicit interface implementation methods are inherited from the base method, so they cannot be specified directly
Rules.Description: When a generic method that is part of a derived class overrides a method in the base class, you may not specify constraints on the overridden method. The override method in the derived class inherits its constraints from the method in the base class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Constraints for override and explicit interface implementation methods are inherited from the base method, so they cannot be specified directly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0460

Rules.Title: The inherited members 'member1' and 'member2' have the same signature in type 'type', so they cannot be overridden
Rules.Description: This error arises with the introduction of generics. Normally, you cannot have two versions of a method in a class with the same signature. But with generics, you can specify a generic method that might duplicate another method if it is instantiated with a particular type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The inherited members 'member1' and 'member2' have the same signature in type 'type', so they cannot be overridden - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0462

Rules.Title: Evaluation of the decimal constant expression failed with error: 'error'
Rules.Description: This errors occurs when a constant decimal expression overflows at compile time.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Evaluation of the decimal constant expression failed with error: 'error' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0463

Rules.Title: 'method1' should not have a params parameter since 'method2' does not
Rules.Description: You cannot use params parameter on a class member if the implemented interface doesn't use it.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'method1' should not have a params parameter since 'method2' does not - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0466

Rules.Title: Ambiguity between type 'type1' and type 'type2'
Rules.Description: This error is generated when there are two types in the assembly being compiled that have the same fully qualified name. This could occur if they are both in added modules or one is in an added module and one in source.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Ambiguity between type 'type1' and type 'type2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0468

Rules.Title: Method 'method' cannot implement interface accessor 'accessor' for type 'type'. Use an explicit interface implementation.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when an accessor is trying to implement an interface. Explicit interface implementation must be used.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Method 'method' cannot implement interface accessor 'accessor' for type 'type'. Use an explicit interface implementation. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0470

Rules.Title: The method 'name' is not a generic method. If you intended an expression list, use parentheses around the < expression.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when your code contains an expression list without parentheses.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The method 'name' is not a generic method. If you intended an expression list, use parentheses around the < expression. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0471

Rules.Title: Explicit interface implementation 'method name' matches more than one interface member. Which interface member is actually chosen is implementation-dependent. Consider using a non-explicit implementation instead.
Rules.Description: In some cases a generic method might acquire the same signature as a non-generic method. The problem is that there is no way in the common language infrastructure (CLI) metadata system to unambiguously state which method binds to which slot. It is up to the CLI to make that determination.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Explicit interface implementation 'method name' matches more than one interface member. Which interface member is actually chosen is implementation-dependent. Consider using a non-explicit implementation instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0473

Rules.Title: 'class member' cannot declare a body because it is marked abstract
Rules.Description: An abstract method cannot contain its implementation.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class member' cannot declare a body because it is marked abstract - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0500

Rules.Title: 'member function' must declare a body because it is not marked abstract, extern, or partial
Rules.Description: Nonabstract methods must have implementations.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member function' must declare a body because it is not marked abstract, extern, or partial - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0501

Rules.Title: 'member' cannot be both abstract and sealed
Rules.Description: A class member cannot be both abstract and sealed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member' cannot be both abstract and sealed - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0502

Rules.Title: The abstract method 'method' cannot be marked virtual
Rules.Description: It is redundant to mark a member method as both abstract and virtual because abstract implies virtual.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The abstract method 'method' cannot be marked virtual - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0503

Rules.Title: The constant 'variable' cannot be marked static
Rules.Description: If a variable is const, it is also static. If you want a const and static variable, just declare that variable as const; if all you want is a static variable, just mark it static.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The constant 'variable' cannot be marked static - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0504

Rules.Title: 'member1': cannot override because 'member2' is not a function
Rules.Description: A class declaration attempted to override a non-method in a base class. Overrides must match the member type. If a method with the same name as a method in a base class is desired, use new (and not override) on the method declaration in the base class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member1': cannot override because 'member2' is not a function - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0505

Rules.Title: 'function1' : cannot override inherited member 'function2' because it is not marked "virtual", "abstract", or "override"
Rules.Description: A method was overridden that was not explicitly marked as virtual, abstract, or override.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'function1' : cannot override inherited member 'function2' because it is not marked "virtual", "abstract", or "override" - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0506

Rules.Title: 'function1' : cannot change access modifiers when overriding 'access' inherited member 'function2'
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to change the access specification in a method override.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'function1' : cannot change access modifiers when overriding 'access' inherited member 'function2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0507

Rules.Title: 'Type 1': return type must be 'Type 2' to match overridden member 'Member Name'
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to change the return type in a method override. To resolve this error, make sure both methods declare the same return type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Type 1': return type must be 'Type 2' to match overridden member 'Member Name' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0508

Rules.Title: 'class1' : cannot derive from sealed type 'class2'
Rules.Description: A sealed class cannot act as a base class. Structs are sealed by default.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class1' : cannot derive from sealed type 'class2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0509

Rules.Title: 'function' is abstract but it is contained in nonabstract class 'class'
Rules.Description: A method cannot be an abstract member of a nonabstract class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'function' is abstract but it is contained in nonabstract class 'class' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0513

Rules.Title: 'constructor' : static constructor cannot have an explicit 'this' or 'base' constructor call
Rules.Description: Calling this in the static constructor is not allowed because the static constructor is called automatically before creating any instance of the class. Also, static constructors are not inherited, and cannot be called directly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'constructor' : static constructor cannot have an explicit 'this' or 'base' constructor call - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0514

Rules.Title: 'function' : access modifiers are not allowed on static constructors
Rules.Description: A static constructor cannot have an access modifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'function' : access modifiers are not allowed on static constructors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0515

Rules.Title: Constructor 'constructor' can not call itself
Rules.Description: A program cannot recursively call constructors.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Constructor 'constructor' can not call itself - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0516

Rules.Title: 'class' has no base class and cannot call a base constructor
Rules.Description: CS0517 can occur only when the .NET runtime compiles the source code for the object class, which is the only class that has no base class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'class' has no base class and cannot call a base constructor - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0517

Rules.Title: Predefined type 'type' is not defined or imported
Rules.Description: The main cause for this problem is that the project is not importing mscorlib.dll, which defines the entire System namespace. This can be caused by one of the following:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Predefined type 'type' is not defined or imported - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0518

Rules.Title: Predefined type 'name' is declared incorrectly
Rules.Description: One or more files needed by the compiler were not found. Reinstall the .NET runtime.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Predefined type 'name' is declared incorrectly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0520

Rules.Title: 'constructor' : structs cannot call base class constructors
Rules.Description: A struct cannot call a base class constructor; remove the call to the base class constructor.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'constructor' : structs cannot call base class constructors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0522

Rules.Title: Struct member 'struct2 field' of type 'struct1' causes a cycle in the struct layout
Rules.Description: The definitions of two structs include recursive references. Change the struct definitions such that each does not define itself on the other. This limitation applies only to structs, since structs are value types. If using recursive references, declare your types as classes.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Struct member 'struct2 field' of type 'struct1' causes a cycle in the struct layout - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0523

Rules.Title: 'type' : interfaces cannot declare types
Rules.Description: An interface cannot contain a user-defined type; it should contain only methods and properties.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type' : interfaces cannot declare types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0524

Rules.Title: Interfaces cannot contain fields
Rules.Description: An interface can contain methods and properties but not fields.

Rules.Title: Interfaces cannot contain constructors
