Rules.TitleAndLink: - Identifier too long - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0645

Rules.Title: Cannot specify the DefaultMember attribute on a type containing an indexer
Rules.Description: If a class or other type specifies System.Reflection.DefaultMemberAttribute, it cannot contain an indexer. For more information, see Properties.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot specify the DefaultMember attribute on a type containing an indexer - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0646

Rules.Title: Error emitting 'attribute' attribute -- 'reason'
Rules.Description: The following sample generates CS0647:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Error emitting 'attribute' attribute -- 'reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0647

Rules.Title: 'type' is a type not supported by the language
Rules.Description: Metadata that was generated from another language, possibly C++, contained a type that was not marked as managed. Information about this type is included in the metadata, but the type is not available to programs written in C#.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type' is a type not supported by the language - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0648

Rules.Title: Bad array declarator: To declare a managed array the rank specifier precedes the variable's identifier. To declare a fixed size buffer field, use the fixed keyword before the field type.
Rules.Description: An array was declared incorrectly. In C#, unlike in C and C++, the square brackets follow the type, not the variable name. Also, realize that the syntax for a fixed size buffer differs from that of an array.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Bad array declarator: To declare a managed array the rank specifier precedes the variable's identifier. To declare a fixed size buffer field, use the fixed keyword before the field type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0650

Rules.Title: Cannot apply attribute class 'class' because it is abstract
Rules.Description: An abstract custom attribute class cannot be used as an attribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot apply attribute class 'class' because it is abstract - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0653

Rules.Title: 'parameter' is not a valid named attribute argument because it is not a valid attribute parameter type
Rules.Description: See Attributes for a discussion of valid parameter types for an attribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'parameter' is not a valid named attribute argument because it is not a valid attribute parameter type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0655

Rules.Title: Missing compiler required member 'object.member'
Rules.Description: One of the following problems exists:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Missing compiler required member 'object.member' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0656

Rules.Title: 'method' cannot specify only Out attribute on a ref parameter. Use both In and Out attributes, or neither.
Rules.Description: An interface method has a parameter that uses ref with just the Out attribute. A ref parameter that uses the Out attribute must also use the In attribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'method' cannot specify only Out attribute on a ref parameter. Use both In and Out attributes, or neither. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0662

Rules.Title: Cannot define overloaded methods that differ only on ref and out.
Rules.Description: Methods that differ only on their use of in, ref and out on a parameter are not allowed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot define overloaded methods that differ only on ref and out. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0663

Rules.Title: Literal of type double cannot be implicitly converted to type 'type'; use an 'suffix' suffix to create a literal of this type
Rules.Description: An assignment could not be completed; use a suffix to correct the instruction. The documentation for each type identifies the corresponding suffix for the type. For more information on conversions, see Casting and Type Conversions.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Literal of type double cannot be implicitly converted to type 'type'; use an 'suffix' suffix to create a literal of this type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0664

Rules.Title: 'member' : new protected member declared in struct
Rules.Description: A struct cannot be abstract and is always implicitly sealed. Because structs do not support inheritance, the concept of a protected member in a struct makes no sense. For more information, see Inheritance.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member' : new protected member declared in struct - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0666

Rules.Title: The feature 'invalid feature' is deprecated. Please use 'valid feature' instead'.
Rules.Description: The feature you are attempting to use is now deprecated. Update your code to use the valid feature instead.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The feature 'invalid feature' is deprecated. Please use 'valid feature' instead'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0667

Rules.Title: Two indexers have different names; the IndexerName attribute must be used with the same name on every indexer within a type
Rules.Description: The values passed to the IndexerName attribute must be the same for all indexers in a type. For more information on the IndexerName attribute, see IndexerNameAttribute Class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Two indexers have different names; the IndexerName attribute must be used with the same name on every indexer within a type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0668

Rules.Title: A class with the ComImport attribute cannot have a user-defined constructor.
Rules.Description: The COM interop layer in the common language runtime supplies the constructor for ComImport classes. Consequently, a COM object can be used as a managed object in the runtime.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A class with the ComImport attribute cannot have a user-defined constructor. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0669

Rules.Title: Field cannot have void type
Rules.Description: A field was declared to be of type void.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Field cannot have void type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0670

Rules.Title: System.Void cannot be used from C# -- use typeof(void) to get the void type object.
Rules.Description: System.Void cannot be used in C#.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - System.Void cannot be used from C# -- use typeof(void) to get the void type object. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0673

Rules.Title: Do not use 'System.ParamArrayAttribute'. Use the 'params' keyword instead.
Rules.Description: The C# compiler does not allow for the use of System.ParamArrayAttribute; use params instead.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Do not use 'System.ParamArrayAttribute'. Use the 'params' keyword instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0674

Rules.Title: 'variable': a volatile field cannot be of the type 'type'
Rules.Description: Fields declared with the volatile keyword must be one of the following types:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'variable': a volatile field cannot be of the type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0677

Rules.Title: 'variable': a field can not be both volatile and readonly
Rules.Description: Use of the volatile and readonly keywords is mutually exclusive.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'variable': a field can not be both volatile and readonly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0678

Rules.Title: The modifier 'abstract' is not valid on fields. Try using a property instead
Rules.Description: You cannot make a field abstract. You can, however, have an abstract property that accesses the field.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The modifier 'abstract' is not valid on fields. Try using a property instead - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0681

Rules.Title: 'type1' cannot implement 'type2' because it is not supported by the language
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you try to implement an interface written in another language and the compiler does not support the interface.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type1' cannot implement 'type2' because it is not supported by the language - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0682

Rules.Title: 'explicitmethod' explicit method implementation cannot implement 'method' because it is an accessor
Rules.Description: The following sample generates CS0683:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'explicitmethod' explicit method implementation cannot implement 'method' because it is an accessor - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0683

Rules.Title: Conditional member 'member' cannot have an out parameter
Rules.Description: When using the ConditionalAttribute attribute on a method, that method may not have an out parameter. This is because the value of the variable used for the out parameter would not be defined in the case that the method call is compiled to nothing. To avoid this error, remove the out parameter from the conditional method declaration, or don't use the Conditional Attribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Conditional member 'member' cannot have an out parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0685

Rules.Title: Accessor 'accessor' cannot implement interface member 'member' for type 'type'. Use an explicit interface implementation.
Rules.Description: Suggested: This error can occur when implementing an interface that contains method names which conflict with the auto-generated methods associated with a property or event. The get/set methods for properties are generated as get_property and set_property, and the add/remove methods for events are generated as add_event and remove_event. If an interface contains either of these methods, a conflict occurs. To avoid this error, implement the methods using an explicit interface implementation. To do this, specify the function as:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Accessor 'accessor' cannot implement interface member 'member' for type 'type'. Use an explicit interface implementation. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0686

Rules.Title: The namespace alias qualifier '::' always resolves to a type or namespace so is illegal here. Consider using '.' instead.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you used something which the parser interpreted as a type in an unexpected place. A type or namespace name is valid only in a member access expression, using the member access (.) operator. This could occur if you used the global scope operator (::) in another context.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The namespace alias qualifier '::' always resolves to a type or namespace so is illegal here. Consider using '.' instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0687

Rules.Title: Cannot derive from 'identifier' because it is a type parameter
Rules.Description: Base classes or interfaces for generic classes cannot be specified by a type parameter. Derive from a specific class or interface, or a specific generic class instead, or include the unknown type as a member.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot derive from 'identifier' because it is a type parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0689

Rules.Title: Input file 'file' contains invalid metadata.
Rules.Description: You are able to open the metadata file, but due to some localization problem, the metadata was corrupted. This is similar to error CS0009, except that you are able to open the metadata file.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Input file 'file' contains invalid metadata. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0690

Rules.Title: Duplicate type parameter 'identifier'
Rules.Description: The same name may not be used more than once in a type parameter list. Rename or remove the duplicate type parameter(s).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Duplicate type parameter 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0692

Rules.Title: Type parameter 'identifier' has the same name as the containing type, or method
Rules.Description: You must use a different name for the type parameter since the type parameter's name cannot be identical to the type or method name that contains the type parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type parameter 'identifier' has the same name as the containing type, or method - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0694

Rules.Title: 'generic type' cannot implement both 'generic interface' and 'generic interface' because they may unify for some type parameter substitutions
Rules.Description: This error occurs when a generic class implements more than one parameterization of the same generic interface, and there exists a type parameter substitution which would make the two interfaces identical. To avoid this error, implement only one of the interfaces, or change the type parameters to avoid the conflict.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'generic type' cannot implement both 'generic interface' and 'generic interface' because they may unify for some type parameter substitutions - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0695

Rules.Title: A generic type cannot derive from 'class' because it is an attribute class
Rules.Description: Any class that derives from an attribute class is an attribute. Attributes are not allowed to be generic types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A generic type cannot derive from 'class' because it is an attribute class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0698

Rules.Title: 'generic' does not define type parameter 'identifier'
Rules.Description: A type parameter was used in a generic definition that was not found in the declaration list of the type parameters for that generic. This can happen if the name used for the type parameter was inconsistent.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'generic' does not define type parameter 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0699

Rules.Title: 'identifier' is not a valid constraint. A type used as a constraint must be an interface, a non-sealed class or a type parameter.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a sealed type is used as a constraint. To resolve this error, use only non-sealed types as constraints.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'identifier' is not a valid constraint. A type used as a constraint must be an interface, a non-sealed class or a type parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0701

Rules.Title: Constraint cannot be special class 'identifier'
Rules.Description: The following types may not be used as constraints:  Object, Array, or ValueType.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Constraint cannot be special class 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0702

Rules.Title: Inconsistent accessibility: constraint type 'identifier' is less accessible than 'identifier'
Rules.Description: A constraint may not force the generic parameter to be less accessible than the generic class itself. In the following example, while the generic class C<T> is declared public, the constraint attempts to force T to implement an internal interface. Even if this were allowed, only clients with internal access would be able to create the parameter for the class, so in effect, the class could be used only by clients with internal access.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent accessibility: constraint type 'identifier' is less accessible than 'identifier' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0703

Rules.Title: Cannot do member lookup in 'type' because it is a type parameter
Rules.Description: An inner type cannot be specified through a type parameter. Try using the desired type explicitly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot do member lookup in 'type' because it is a type parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0704

Rules.Title: Invalid constraint type. A type used as a constraint must be an interface, a non-sealed class or a type parameter.
Rules.Description: This error occurs when an invalid construct is used in a constraint clause. To avoid this error, use an interface or non-sealed class instead of the construct that caused the error.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid constraint type. A type used as a constraint must be an interface, a non-sealed class or a type parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0706

Rules.Title: 'field': cannot declare instance members in a static class
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you declare a non-static member in a class that is declared static. It is not possible to create instances of static classes, so instance variables would not be meaningful. The static keyword should be applied to all members of static classes.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'field': cannot declare instance members in a static class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0708

Rules.Title: 'derived class': cannot derive from static class 'base class'
Rules.Description: A static class cannot be instantiated or derived from. That is, a static class cannot be a base class of any other class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'derived class': cannot derive from static class 'base class' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0709

Rules.Title: Static classes cannot have instance constructors
Rules.Description: A static class cannot be instantiated, hence it has no need for constructors. To avoid this error, remove any constructors from static classes, or if you really want to construct instances, make the class non-static.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Static classes cannot have instance constructors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0710

Rules.Title: Static classes cannot contain destructors
Rules.Description: A static class cannot be instantiated, hence it has no need for constructors or finalizer. To avoid this error, remove finalizer from static classes, or, if you really want to construct and destroy instances, make the class non-static.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Static classes cannot contain destructors - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0711

Rules.Title: Cannot create an instance of the static class 'static class'
Rules.Description: It is not possible to create instances of static classes. Static classes are designed to contain static fields and methods, but may not be instantiated.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot create an instance of the static class 'static class' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0712

Rules.Title: Static class 'static type' cannot derive from type 'type'. Static classes must derive from object.
Rules.Description: If this were allowed, the static class would inherit methods and non-static members from the base class, so it would not be static. Therefore, it is not allowed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Static class 'static type' cannot derive from type 'type'. Static classes must derive from object. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0713

Rules.Title: 'static type' : static classes cannot implement interfaces
Rules.Description: Interfaces may define non-static methods on objects and hence may not be implemented by static classes. To resolve this error, make sure your class does not attempt to implement any interfaces.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'static type' : static classes cannot implement interfaces - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0714

Rules.Title: 'static class' : static classes cannot contain user defined operators
Rules.Description: User defined operators operate on instances of classes. Static classes cannot be instantiated, so it is not possible to create instances for operators to act upon. Hence, user defined operators are not allowed for static classes.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'static class' : static classes cannot contain user defined operators - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0715

Rules.Title: Cannot convert to static type 'type'
Rules.Description: This error occurs if your code uses a cast to convert to a static type. Since it is not possible for an object to be an instance of a static type, casting to a static type can never be a meaningful cast.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert to static type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0716

Rules.Title: 'static class': static classes cannot be used as constraints
Rules.Description: Static classes cannot be extended as they only contain static members and not instance members. Because they cannot be extended, this makes them useless as type parameters and constraints, as no type can exist that is a specialization of a static class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'static class': static classes cannot be used as constraints - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0717

Rules.Title: 'type': static types cannot be used as type arguments
Rules.Description: Because a static type cannot be instantiated, it cannot be used as a generic argument. To resolve this error, remove the static type from the generic argument.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type': static types cannot be used as type arguments - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0718

Rules.Title: 'type': array elements cannot be of static type
Rules.Description: An array of static type does not make sense since array elements are instances, but it is not possible to create instances of static types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type': array elements cannot be of static type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0719

Rules.Title: 'static class': cannot declare indexers in a static class
Rules.Description: Indexers are not meaningful in static classes, since they can only be used with instances, and it is not possible to create instances of a static type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'static class': cannot declare indexers in a static class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0720

Rules.Title: 'type': static types cannot be used as parameters
Rules.Description: A static type is not meaningful as a parameter. Since no instances of static types may be created, no instance could ever be passed as a parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type': static types cannot be used as parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0721

Rules.Title: 'type': static types cannot be used as return types
Rules.Description: A static type as a return type is not meaningful since instances of static types cannot be created.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type': static types cannot be used as return types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0722

Rules.Title: Cannot declare variable of static type 'type'
Rules.Description: Instances of static types cannot be created.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot declare variable of static type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0723

Rules.Title: A throw statement with no arguments is not allowed in a finally clause that is nested inside the nearest enclosing catch clause
Rules.Description: The following example generates CS0724 because of the throw statement inside the finally clause block:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A throw statement with no arguments is not allowed in a finally clause that is nested inside the nearest enclosing catch clause - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0724

Rules.Title: 'format specifier' is not a valid format specifier
Rules.Description: This error occurs in the debugger. When you type a variable name into one of the debugger windows, you can follow it with a comma, and then a format specifier. Examples are: myInt, h or myString,nq. This error arises when the compiler does not recognize the Format Specifiers in C#.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'format specifier' is not a valid format specifier - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0726

Rules.Title: Invalid format specifier
Rules.Description: This error occurs in the debugger. When you type a variable name into one of the debugger windows, you can follow it with a comma, and then a format specifier. Examples are: myInt, h; or myString,nq. This error arises when the compiler is completely unable to parse what you typed in. To resolve this error, retype the variable name, optionally followed by a comma and a valid Format Specifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid format specifier - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0727

Rules.Title: Type 'type' is defined in this assembly, but a type forwarder is specified for it
Rules.Description: You cannot use a type forwarder for a type defined in the same assembly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type 'type' is defined in this assembly, but a type forwarder is specified for it - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0729

Rules.Title: Cannot forward type 'type' because it is a nested type of 'type'
Rules.Description: This error is generated when you try to forward a nested class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot forward type 'type' because it is a nested type of 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0730

Rules.Title: The type forwarder for type 'type' in assembly 'assembly' causes a cycle
Rules.Description: This error can only occur with improperly formed imported metadata. It cannot occur with only C# source.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type forwarder for type 'type' in assembly 'assembly' causes a cycle - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0731

Rules.Title: Cannot forward generic type, 'GenericType<>'
Rules.Description: The following example generates CS0733. Compile the first file as a library, and then reference it when you compile the second file.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot forward generic type, 'GenericType<>' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0733

Rules.Title: The /moduleassemblyname option may only be specified when building a target type of 'module'
Rules.Description: The compiler option ModuleAssemblyName should only be used when building a .netmodule. See ModuleAssemblyName (C# Compiler Option) for more information.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The /moduleassemblyname option may only be specified when building a target type of 'module' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0734

Rules.Title: Invalid type specified as an argument for TypeForwardedTo attribute
Rules.Description: The following sample generates CS0735.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid type specified as an argument for TypeForwardedTo attribute - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0735

Rules.Title: 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement an interface member because it is static.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when a static method is either implicitly or explicitly declared as an implementation of an interface member.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement an interface member because it is static. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0736

Rules.Title: 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement an interface member because it is not public.
Rules.Description: A method that implements an interface member must have public accessibility. All interface members are public.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement an interface member because it is not public. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0737

Rules.Title: 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement 'interface member' because it does not have the matching return type of ' type name'.
Rules.Description: The return value of an implementing method in a class must match the return value of the interface member that it implements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type name' does not implement interface member 'member name'. 'method name' cannot implement 'interface member' because it does not have the matching return type of ' type name'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0738

Rules.Title: 'type name' duplicate TypeForwardedToAttribute.
Rules.Description: An assembly can have no more than one TypeForwardedToAttribute to an external type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type name' duplicate TypeForwardedToAttribute. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0739

Rules.Title: A query body must end with a select clause or a group clause
Rules.Description: A query expression must terminate with either a select clause or a group clause without a continuation.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A query body must end with a select clause or a group clause - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0742

Rules.Description: The pattern for a join clause is join...in...on...equals, as shown in this example:

Rules.Title: Expected contextual keyword 'equals'
Rules.Description: The pattern for a join clause is join...in...on...equals, as shown in this example:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expected contextual keyword 'equals' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0744

Rules.Title: Expected contextual keyword 'by'
Rules.Description: The pattern for the group clause is group...by followed by an optional into, as shown in the following example:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expected contextual keyword 'by' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0745

Rules.Title: Invalid anonymous type member declarator. Anonymous type members must be declared with a member assignment, simple name or member access.
Rules.Description: An anonymous type must be declared with a member assignment, simple name, or member access.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid anonymous type member declarator. Anonymous type members must be declared with a member assignment, simple name or member access. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0746

Rules.Title: Invalid initializer member declarator.
Rules.Description: An object initializer is used to assign values to properties or fields. Any expression which is not an assignment to a property or field is a compile-time error.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid initializer member declarator. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0747

Rules.Title: Inconsistent lambda parameter usage; parameter types must be all explicit or all implicit.
Rules.Description: If a lambda expression has multiple input parameters, some parameters cannot use implicit typing while others use explicit typing.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Inconsistent lambda parameter usage; parameter types must be all explicit or all implicit. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0748

Rules.Title: A partial method cannot have access modifiers or the virtual, abstract, override, new, sealed, or extern modifiers.
Rules.Description: Because of their special behavior, partial methods are subject to restrictions as to the modifiers they can accept.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method cannot have access modifiers or the virtual, abstract, override, new, sealed, or extern modifiers. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0750

Rules.Title: A partial method must be declared in a partial class or partial struct
Rules.Description: It is not possible to declare a partial method unless it is encapsulated inside a partial class or partial struct.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method must be declared in a partial class or partial struct - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0751

Rules.Title: A partial method cannot have out parameters
Rules.Description: A partial method cannot have an out parameter. Out parameters are not allowed because if the partial method is removed by the compiler then there is no guarantee that the out parameter is ever assigned.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method cannot have out parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0752

Rules.Title: Only methods, classes, structs, or interfaces may be partial.
Rules.Description: The partial modifier can only be used with classes, structs, interfaces, and methods.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Only methods, classes, structs, or interfaces may be partial. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0753

Rules.Title: A partial method may not explicitly implement an interface method.
Rules.Description: A partial method cannot be declared as an explicit implementation of a method defined in an interface.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method may not explicitly implement an interface method. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0754

Rules.Title: Both partial method declarations must be extension methods or neither may be an extension method.
Rules.Description: A partial method consists of a defining declaration (signature) and an optional implementing declaration (body). If the defining declaration is an extension method, the implementing declaration, if one is defined, must also be an extension method. And if the defining method is not an extension method, the implementing must not be one either.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Both partial method declarations must be extension methods or neither may be an extension method. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0755

Rules.Title: A partial method may not have multiple defining declarations.
Rules.Description: The defining declaration of a partial method is the part that specifies the method signature, but not the implementation (method body). A partial method must have exactly one defining declaration for each unique signature. Each overloaded version of a partial method must have its own defining declaration.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method may not have multiple defining declarations. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0756

Rules.Title: A partial method may not have multiple implementing declarations.
Rules.Description: A partial method consists of exactly one defining declaration (signature) and one or zero implementing declarations (body). Multiple implementing declarations for the same identical defining declarations are not allowed. Partial methods may be overloaded, and each overloaded version may have one or zero implementing declarations.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A partial method may not have multiple implementing declarations. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0757

Rules.Title: Both partial method declarations must use a params parameter or neither may use a params parameter
Rules.Description: If one part of a partial method specifies a params parameter, the other part must specify one also.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Both partial method declarations must use a params parameter or neither may use a params parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0758

Rules.Title: No defining declaration found for implementing declaration of partial method 'method'.
Rules.Description: A partial method must have a defining declaration that defines the signature (name, return type and parameters) of the method. The implementation or method body is optional.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - No defining declaration found for implementing declaration of partial method 'method'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0759

Rules.Title: Partial method declarations of 'method<T>' have inconsistent type parameter constraints.
Rules.Description: If a partial method has an implementation, the generic type constraint must be identical to the constraint defined on the method signature.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Partial method declarations of 'method<T>' have inconsistent type parameter constraints. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0761

Rules.Title: Cannot create delegate from method 'method' because it is a partial method without an implementing declaration
Rules.Description: A partial method is not required to have an implementing declaration. However, a delegate does require that its encapsulated method have an implementation.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot create delegate from method 'method' because it is a partial method without an implementing declaration - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0762

Rules.Title: Both partial method declarations must be static or neither may be static.
Rules.Description: A partial method declaration cannot have one part static and the other part not static.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Both partial method declarations must be static or neither may be static. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0763

Rules.Title: Both partial method declarations must be unsafe or neither may be unsafe
Rules.Description: A partial method consists of a defining declaration (signature) and an optional implementing declaration (body). If the defining declaration has the unsafe modifier, the implementing declaration must also have it. Conversely, if the implementing declaration has the unsafe modifier, the defining declaration must also.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Both partial method declarations must be unsafe or neither may be unsafe - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0764

Rules.Title: Partial methods with only a defining declaration or removed conditional methods cannot be used in expression trees
Rules.Description: Although a call to a removed partial method is an expression, it is not an acceptable expression in an expression tree.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Partial methods with only a defining declaration or removed conditional methods cannot be used in expression trees - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0765

Rules.Title: Partial methods must have a void return type.
Rules.Description: A partial method cannot return a value. Its return type must be void.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Partial methods must have a void return type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0766

Rules.Title: The fully qualified name for 'name' is too long for debug information. Compile without '/debug' option.
Rules.Description: There are size constraints on variable and type names in debug information.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The fully qualified name for 'name' is too long for debug information. Compile without '/debug' option. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0811

Rules.Title: Cannot assign 'expression' to an implicitly typed local
Rules.Description:
An expression that is used as the initializer for an implicitly typed variable must have a type. Because anonymous function expressions, method group expressions, and the null literal expression do not have a type, they are not appropriate initializers. An implicitly typed variable cannot be initialized with a null value in its declaration, although it can later be assigned a value of null.
With C# version 10 Lambda expressions and method groups with natural types can be used as initializers in var declarations.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign 'expression' to an implicitly typed local - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0815

Rules.Title: Implicitly typed locals must be initialized
Rules.Description: An implicitly typed local variable must be initialized with a value at the same time that it is declared.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Implicitly typed locals must be initialized - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0818

Rules.Title: Implicitly-typed variables cannot have multiple declarators.
Rules.Description: Multiple declarators are allowed in explicit type declarations, but not with implicitly typed variables.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Implicitly-typed variables cannot have multiple declarators. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0819

Rules.Title: Cannot assign array initializer to an implicitly typed local
Rules.Description: An implicitly typed array is an array whose element type is inferred by the compiler. It must be initialized by using the new[] modifier as shown in the example code.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign array initializer to an implicitly typed local - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0820

Rules.Title: Implicitly typed locals cannot be fixed
Rules.Description: Implicitly typed local variables and anonymous types are not supported in the fixed context.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Implicitly typed locals cannot be fixed - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0821

Rules.Title: Implicitly typed locals cannot be const
Rules.Description: Implicitly typed local variables are only necessary for storing anonymous types. In all other cases they are just a convenience. If the value of the variable never changes, just give it an explicit type. Attempting to use the readonly modifier with an implicitly typed local will generate CS0106.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Implicitly typed locals cannot be const - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0822

Rules.Title: The contextual keyword 'var' may only appear within a local variable declaration.
Rules.Description: The following code generates CS0825 because var is used on a class field:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The contextual keyword 'var' may only appear within a local variable declaration. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0825

Rules.Title: No best type found for implicitly typed array.
Rules.Description: Array elements must all be the same type or implicitly convertible to the same type according to the type inference rules used by the compiler. The best type must be one of the types present in the array expression. Elements will not be converted to a new type such as object. For an implicitly typed array, the compiler must infer the array type based on the type of elements assigned to it.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - No best type found for implicitly typed array. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0826

Rules.Title: Cannot assign 'expression' to anonymous type property.
Rules.Description: An anonymous type cannot be initialized with a null value or an unsafe type, or a method group or anonymous function.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign 'expression' to anonymous type property. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0828

Rules.Title: An expression tree may not contain a base access.
Rules.Description: A base access means to make a function call that would ordinarily be a virtual function call as a non-virtual function call on the base class method. This is not allowed in the expression tree itself, but you can invoke a helper method in your class that invokes the base class method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree may not contain a base access. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0831

Rules.Title: An expression tree may not contain an assignment operator.
Rules.Description: An expression tree does not preserve variable state or have any concept of a storage location.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree may not contain an assignment operator. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0832

Rules.Title: An anonymous type cannot have multiple properties with the same name.
Rules.Description: An anonymous type, just like any type, cannot have two properties that have the same name.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An anonymous type cannot have multiple properties with the same name. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0833

Rules.Title: A lambda expression must have an expression body to be converted to an expression tree.
Rules.Description: Lambdas that are translated to expression trees must be expression lambdas; statement lambdas and anonymous methods can only be converted to delegate types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A lambda expression must have an expression body to be converted to an expression tree. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0834

Rules.Title: Cannot convert lambda to an expression tree whose type argument 'type' is not a delegate type.
Rules.Description: If a lambda expression is converted to an expression tree, the expression tree must have a delegate type for its argument. Furthermore, the lambda expression must be convertible to the delegate type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert lambda to an expression tree whose type argument 'type' is not a delegate type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0835

Rules.Title: Cannot use anonymous type in a constant expression.
Rules.Description: The only things allowed in a constant expression are named constants, literals, and mathematical expressions that combine constant expressions.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use anonymous type in a constant expression. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0836

Rules.Title: The first operand of an 'is' or 'as' operator may not be a lambda expression, anonymous method, or method group.
Rules.Description: Lambda expressions, anonymous methods and method groups may not be used on the left side of is or as.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The first operand of an 'is' or 'as' operator may not be a lambda expression, anonymous method, or method group. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0837

Rules.Title: An expression tree may not contain a multidimensional array initializer.
Rules.Description: Multidimensional arrays in expression trees cannot be initialized by using an array initializer.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree may not contain a multidimensional array initializer. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0838

Rules.Title: Argument missing.
Rules.Description: An argument is missing in the method call.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Argument missing. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0839

Rules.Title: 'Property name' must declare a body because it is not marked abstract or extern. Automatically implemented properties must define both get and set accessors.
Rules.Description: Unless a regular property is marked as abstract or extern, or is a member of a partial type, it must supply a body. Auto-implemented properties do not provide accessor bodies, but they must specify both accessors. To create a read-only auto-implemented property, make the set accessor private.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Property name' must declare a body because it is not marked abstract or extern. Automatically implemented properties must define both get and set accessors. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0840

Rules.Title: Cannot use local variable 'name' before it is declared.
Rules.Description: A variable must be declared before it is used.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use local variable 'name' before it is declared. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0841

Rules.Title: Automatically implemented properties cannot be used inside a type marked with StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit).
Rules.Description: Auto-implemented properties have their backing fields provided by the compiler and the field is not accessible to source code. Therefore, they are not compatible with LayoutKind.Explicit.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Automatically implemented properties cannot be used inside a type marked with StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit). - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0842

Rules.Title: Backing field for automatically implemented property 'name' must be fully assigned before control is returned to the caller. Consider calling the parameterless constructor from a constructor initializer.
Rules.Description: To assign a value to an automatically-implemented property from a constructor, you must first invoke the parameterless constructor to create the object.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Backing field for automatically implemented property 'name' must be fully assigned before control is returned to the caller. Consider calling the parameterless constructor from a constructor initializer. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0843

Rules.Title: Cannot use local variable 'name' before it is declared. The declaration of the local variable hides the field 'name'.
Rules.Description: An identifier can have only one meaning in a given block. Local variables that have the same name as class fields can hide the field by introducing a second meaning for the identifier. Therefore the compiler generates an error when you refer to a class field in a method, and then declare a local variable by the same name.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use local variable 'name' before it is declared. The declaration of the local variable hides the field 'name'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0844

Rules.Title: An expression tree lambda may not contain a coalescing operator with a null literal left-hand side.
Rules.Description: Because null by itself does not have a type, the null coalescing operator cannot operate on it.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree lambda may not contain a coalescing operator with a null literal left-hand side. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0845

Rules.Title: Identifier expected
Rules.Description: You did not supply an identifier. An identifier is the name of a class, struct, namespace, method, variable and so on that you provide.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Identifier expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1001

Rules.Title: ; expected
Rules.Description: The compiler detected a missing semicolon. A semicolon is required at the end of every statement in C#. A statement may span more than one line.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - ; expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1002

Rules.Title: Syntax error, 'char' expected
Rules.Description: The compiler will generate this error for any one of several error conditions. Review your code to find the syntax error.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Syntax error, 'char' expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1003

Rules.Title: Duplicate 'modifier' modifier
Rules.Description: A duplicate modifier, such as an access modifier, was detected.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Duplicate 'modifier' modifier - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1004

Rules.Title: Property accessor already defined
Rules.Description: When you declare a property, you must also declare its accessor methods. However, a property cannot have more than one get accessor method or more than one set accessor method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Property accessor already defined - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1007

Rules.Title: Type byte, sbyte, short, ushort, int, uint, long, or ulong expected
Rules.Description: Certain data types, such as enums, can only be declared to hold data of specified types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type byte, sbyte, short, ushort, int, uint, long, or ulong expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1008

Rules.Title: Unrecognized escape sequence
Rules.Description: An unexpected character follows a backslash (\) in a string. The compiler expects one of the valid escape characters. For more information, see Character Escapes.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unrecognized escape sequence - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1009

Rules.Title: Newline in constant
Rules.Description: A string was not properly delimited.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Newline in constant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1010

Rules.Title: Empty character literal
Rules.Description: A char was declared and initialized to a null. The initialization of a char must specify a character.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Empty character literal - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1011

Rules.Title: Too many characters in character literal
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to initialize a char constant with more than one character.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Too many characters in character literal - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1012

Rules.Title: Invalid number
Rules.Description: The compiler detected a malformed number. For more information on integral types, see the Integral Types Table.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid number - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1013

Rules.Title: A get or set accessor expected
Rules.Description: A method declaration was found in a property declaration. You can only declare get and set methods in a property.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A get or set accessor expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1014

Rules.Title: An object, string, or class type expected
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to pass a predefined data type into a catch block. Only data types that derive from System.Exception can be passed into a catch block. For more information on exceptions, see Exceptions and Exception Handling.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An object, string, or class type expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1015

Rules.Title: Named attribute argument expected
Rules.Description: Unnamed attribute arguments must appear before the named arguments.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Named attribute argument expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1016

Rules.Title: Catch clauses cannot follow the general catch clause of a try statement
Rules.Description: A catch block that does not take any parameters must be the last in a series of catch blocks. For more information on exceptions, see Exceptions and Exception Handling.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Catch clauses cannot follow the general catch clause of a try statement - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1017

Rules.Title: Keyword 'this' or 'base' expected
Rules.Description: The compiler encountered an incomplete constructor declaration.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Keyword 'this' or 'base' expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1018

Rules.Title: Overloadable unary operator expected
Rules.Description: Something that looks like an overloaded unary operator has been declared, but the operator is missing or is in the wrong location in the signature.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Overloadable unary operator expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1019

Rules.Title: Overloadable binary operator expected
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to define an operator overload, but the operator was not an overloadable binary operator, which takes two parameters. For the list of overloadable operators, see the Overloadable operators section of the Operator overloading article.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Overloadable binary operator expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1020

Rules.Title: Integral constant is too large

Rules.TitleAndLink: - Integral constant is too large - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1021

Rules.Title: Type or namespace definition, or end-of-file expected

Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type or namespace definition, or end-of-file expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1022

Rules.Title: Embedded statement cannot be a declaration or labeled statement
Rules.Description: An embedded statement, such as the statements following an if statement, can contain neither declarations nor labeled statements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Embedded statement cannot be a declaration or labeled statement - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1023

Rules.Title: Preprocessor directive expected

Rules.Title: Single-line comment or end-of-line expected

Rules.Title: Unexpected preprocessor directive

Rules.Title: Type expected

Rules.Title: Cannot define/undefine preprocessor symbols after first token in file
Rules.Description: The #define and #undef preprocessor directives must be used at the beginning of a program, before any other keywords, such as those used in the namespace declaration.

Rules.Title: Source file has exceeded the limit of 16,707,565 lines representable in the PDB; debug information will be incorrect
Rules.Description: A source-code file exceeded the maximum allowable number of lines that the compiler can process. To resolve this error, create two or more source-code files from the original file. The maximum number of lines is 268,435,454 lines. If you are using /debug, using more than 16,707,566 will result in corrupted debug information.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Source file has exceeded the limit of 16,707,565 lines representable in the PDB; debug information will be incorrect - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1033

Rules.Title: Compiler limit exceeded: Line cannot exceed 'number' characters
Rules.Description: The limit for the number of characters allowed on a line is 16,777,214.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Compiler limit exceeded: Line cannot exceed 'number' characters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1034

Rules.Title: End-of-file found, '*/' expected

Rules.TitleAndLink: - End-of-file found, '*/' expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1035

Rules.Title: #endregion directive expected
Rules.Description: A #region directive did not have a matching #endregion directive.

Rules.Description: The compiler detected an ill-formed string literal.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unterminated string literal - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1039

Rules.Title: Preprocessor directives must appear as the first non-white-space character on a line
Rules.Description: A preprocessor directive was found on a line and was not the first token on the line. A directive must be the first token on the line.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Preprocessor directives must appear as the first non-white-space character on a line - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1040

Rules.Title: Identifier expected, 'keyword' is a keyword
Rules.Description: A reserved word for the C# language was found where an identifier was expected. Replace the keyword with a user-specified identifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Identifier expected, 'keyword' is a keyword - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1041

Rules.Title: { or ; expected
Rules.Description: A property accessor was declared incorrectly. For more information, see Using Properties.

Rules.Title: Cannot use more than one type in a for, using, fixed, or declaration statement
Rules.Description: The compiler found an invalid statement.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use more than one type in a for, using, fixed, or declaration statement - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1044

Rules.Title: An add or remove accessor expected
Rules.Description: If your event is not declared as a field, it must define both add and remove accessor functions.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An add or remove accessor expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1055

Rules.Title: Unexpected character 'character'
Rules.Description: The C# compiler encountered an unexpected character, and is unable to identify the token currently being processed. For example, if the compiler encounters a Euro-character in the middle of processing an identifier, it will be unable to classify the identifier, since a Euro-character would only be valid inside a string, and the compiler knows it is not processing a string.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected character 'character' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1056

Rules.Title: 'member': static classes cannot contain protected members
Rules.Description: This error is generated by declaring a protected member inside a static class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member': static classes cannot contain protected members - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1057

Rules.Title: The operand of an increment or decrement operator must be a variable, property or indexer.
Rules.Description: This error is raised when you try to increment or decrement a constant value. It can also occur if you try to increment an expression such as (a+b)++.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The operand of an increment or decrement operator must be a variable, property or indexer. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1059

Rules.Title: 'type' does not contain a definition for 'name' and no accessible extension method 'name' accepting a first argument of type 'type' could be found (are you missing a using directive or an assembly reference?).
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you try to call a method or access a class member that does not exist.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type' does not contain a definition for 'name' and no accessible extension method 'name' accepting a first argument of type 'type' could be found (are you missing a using directive or an assembly reference?). - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1061

Rules.Title: Method 'name' has a parameter modifier 'this' which is not on the first parameter.
Rules.Description: The this modifier is allowed only on the first parameter of a method, which indicates to the compiler that the method is an extension method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Method 'name' has a parameter modifier 'this' which is not on the first parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1100

Rules.Title: The parameter modifier 'ref' cannot be used with 'this'.
Rules.Description: When the this keyword modifies the first parameter of a static method, it signals to the compiler that the method is an extension method. No other modifiers are needed or allowed on the first parameter of an extension method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The parameter modifier 'ref' cannot be used with 'this'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1101

Rules.Title: The parameter modifier 'out' cannot be used with 'this'.
Rules.Description: When the this keyword modifies the first parameter of a static method, it signals to the compiler that the method is an extension method. No other modifiers are needed or allowed on the first parameter of an extension method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The parameter modifier 'out' cannot be used with 'this'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1102

Rules.Title: The first parameter of an extension method cannot be of type 'type'.
Rules.Description: The first parameter of an extension method cannot be a pointer type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The first parameter of an extension method cannot be of type 'type'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1103

Rules.Title: A parameter array cannot be used with 'this' modifier on an extension method.
Rules.Description: The first parameter of an extension method cannot be a params array.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A parameter array cannot be used with 'this' modifier on an extension method. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1104

Rules.Title: Extension methods must be static.
Rules.Description: Extension methods must be declared as static methods in a non-generic static class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Extension methods must be static. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1105

Rules.Title: Extension methods must be defined in a non generic static class.
Rules.Description: Extension methods must be defined as static methods in a non-generic static class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Extension methods must be defined in a non generic static class. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1106

Rules.Title: A parameter can only have one 'modifier name' modifier.
Rules.Description: It is an error for parameter modifiers such as this, ref, in, and out to appear more than one time in a parameter definition.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A parameter can only have one 'modifier name' modifier. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1107

Rules.Title: A parameter cannot have all the specified modifiers; there are too many modifiers on the parameter.
Rules.Description: Certain combinations of parameter modifiers, such as in, ref, and out, are not allowed because they have mutually exclusive meanings for the compiler.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A parameter cannot have all the specified modifiers; there are too many modifiers on the parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1108

Rules.Title: Extension Methods must be defined on top level static classes, 'name' is a nested class.
Rules.Description: Extension methods cannot be defined in nested classes.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Extension Methods must be defined on top level static classes, 'name' is a nested class. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1109

Rules.Title: Cannot use 'this' modifier on first parameter of method declaration without a reference to System.Core.dll. Add a reference to System.Core.dll or remove 'this' modifier from the method declaration.
Rules.Description: Extension methods are supported on version 3.5 and later of .NET Framework. Extension methods generate metadata which marks the method with an attribute. The attribute class is in system.core.dll.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use 'this' modifier on first parameter of method declaration without a reference to System.Core.dll. Add a reference to System.Core.dll or remove 'this' modifier from the method declaration. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1110

Rules.Title: Do not use 'System.Runtime.CompilerServices.ExtensionAttribute'. Use the 'this' keyword instead.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when the ExtensionAttribute is used on a non-static class that contains extension methods. If this attribute is used on a static class, another error, such as CS0708: "Cannot declare instance members in a static class," might occur.

Rules.Title: Cannot access protected member 'member' via a qualifier of type 'type1'; the qualifier must be of type 'type2' (or derived from it)

Because protected members can be accessed only by derived types, any attempts to access protected members that might not be valid at run time are marked by the compiler as not valid.
