Rules.Description: Some types in the .NET class library, for example, TypedReference, RuntimeArgumentHandle and ArgIterator cannot be used as in, ref or out parameters because they could potentially be used to perform unsafe operations.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Method or delegate parameter cannot be of type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1601

Rules.Title: Cannot assign to 'variable' because it is read-only
Rules.Description: An assignment was made to a read-only variable. To avoid this error, do not assign or attempt to modify  to this variable in this context.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign to 'variable' because it is read-only - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1604

Rules.Title: Cannot pass 'var' as a ref or out argument because it is read-only
Rules.Description: A variable passed as a ref or out parameter is expected to be modified in the called method. Therefore, it is not possible to pass a read-only parameter as ref or out.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot pass 'var' as a ref or out argument because it is read-only - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1605

Rules.Title: Assembly signing failed; output may not be signed -- reason
Rules.Description: The assembly was produced, but when the compiler attempted to finish signing it, there was a failure.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Assembly signing failed; output may not be signed -- reason - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1606

Rules.Title: The Required attribute is not permitted on C# types
Rules.Description: RequiredAttributeAttribute is not allowed on types defined in C# code.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The Required attribute is not permitted on C# types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1608

Rules.Title: Modifiers cannot be placed on event accessor declarations
Rules.Description: Modifiers can only be placed on event declarations and not on the event accessor declarations. For more information, see Using Properties.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Modifiers cannot be placed on event accessor declarations - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1609

Rules.Title: The params parameter cannot be declared as in ref or out
Rules.Description: The keywords in, ref or out cannot be used with the params keyword.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The params parameter cannot be declared as in ref or out - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1611

Rules.Title: Cannot modify the return value of 'expression' because it is not a variable
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to modify a value type that is produced as the result of an intermediate expression but is not stored in a variable. This error can occur when you attempt to directly modify a struct in a generic collection, as shown in the following example:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot modify the return value of 'expression' because it is not a variable - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1612

Rules.Title: The managed coclass wrapper class 'class' for interface 'interface' cannot be found (are you missing an assembly reference?)
Rules.Description: An attempt was made to instantiate a COM object from an interface. The interface has the ComImport and CoClass attributes, but the compiler cannot find the type given for the CoClass attribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The managed coclass wrapper class 'class' for interface 'interface' cannot be found (are you missing an assembly reference?) - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1613

Rules.Title: 'name' is ambiguous between 'name' and 'nameAttribute'; use either '@name' or 'nameAttribute'.
Rules.Description: The compiler has encountered an ambiguous attribute specification.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'name' is ambiguous between 'name' and 'nameAttribute'; use either '@name' or 'nameAttribute'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1614

Rules.Title: Argument 'number' should not be passed with the 'keyword' keyword
Rules.Description: One of the keywords ref or out was used when the function did not take a ref or out parameter for that argument. To resolve this error, remove the incorrect keyword and use the appropriate keyword that matches the function declaration, if any.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Argument 'number' should not be passed with the 'keyword' keyword - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1615

Rules.Title: Invalid option 'option' for LangVersion. Use <LangVersion>?</LangVersion> to list supported values.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you used the LangVersion command line switch or project setting but didn't specify a valid language option. To resolve this error, check the command line syntax or project setting and change it to one of the listed options.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid option 'option' for LangVersion. Use <LangVersion>?</LangVersion> to list supported values. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1617

Rules.Title: Cannot create delegate with 'method' because it has a Conditional attribute
Rules.Description: You cannot create a delegate with a conditional method because the method might not exist in some builds.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot create delegate with 'method' because it has a Conditional attribute - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1618

Rules.Title: Cannot create temporary file 'filename' -- reason
Rules.Description: The compiler was unable to create a temporary file for the given reason (for example, the disk is full).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot create temporary file 'filename' -- reason - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1619

Rules.Title: Argument 'number' must be passed with the 'keyword' keyword
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you are passing an argument to a function that takes a ref or out parameter and you don't include the ref or out keyword at the point of call, or you include the wrong keyword. The error text indicates the appropriate keyword to use and which argument caused the failure.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Argument 'number' must be passed with the 'keyword' keyword - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1620

Rules.Title: The yield statement cannot be used inside an anonymous method or lambda expression
Rules.Description: You cannot use the yield statement in an anonymous method or a lambda expression.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The yield statement cannot be used inside an anonymous method or lambda expression - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1621

Rules.Title: Cannot return a value from an iterator. Use the yield return statement to return a value, or yield break to end the iteration.
Rules.Description: An iterator is a special function that returns a value via the yield statement rather than the return statement. For more information, see iterators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot return a value from an iterator. Use the yield return statement to return a value, or yield break to end the iteration. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1622

Rules.Title: Iterators cannot have in ref or out parameters
Rules.Description: This error occurs if an iterator method takes an in, ref, or out parameter. To avoid this error, remove the in, ref, or out keyword from the method signature.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Iterators cannot have in ref or out parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1623

Rules.Title: The body of 'accessor' cannot be an iterator block because 'type' is not an iterator interface type
Rules.Description: This error occurs if an iterator accessor is used but the return type is not one of the iterator interface types: IEnumerable, IEnumerable<T>, IEnumerator, IEnumerator<T>. To avoid this error, use one of the iterator interface types as a return type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The body of 'accessor' cannot be an iterator block because 'type' is not an iterator interface type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1624

Rules.Title: Cannot yield in the body of a finally clause
Rules.Description: A yield statement is not allowed in the body of a finally clause. To avoid this error, move the yield statement out of the finally clause.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot yield in the body of a finally clause - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1625

Rules.Title: Cannot yield a value in the body of a try block with a catch clause
Rules.Description: A yield statement is not allowed in a try block if there is a catch clause associated with the try block. To avoid this error, either move the yield statement out of the try/catch/finally block, or remove the catch block.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot yield a value in the body of a try block with a catch clause - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1626

Rules.Title: Expression expected after yield return
Rules.Description: This error occurs if yield is used without an expression. To avoid this error, insert the appropriate expression in the statement.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expression expected after yield return - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1627

Rules.Title: Cannot use in ref or out parameter 'parameter' inside an anonymous method, lambda expression, or query expression
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you use an in, ref, or out parameter inside an anonymous method block. To avoid this error, use a local variable or some other construct.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot use in ref or out parameter 'parameter' inside an anonymous method, lambda expression, or query expression - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1628

Rules.Title: Unsafe code may not appear in iterators
Rules.Description: The C# language specification does not allow unsafe code in iterators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unsafe code may not appear in iterators - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1629

Rules.Title: Invalid option 'option' for ErrorReport; must be prompt, send, queue, or none
Rules.Description: The command line option ErrorReport must be followed by prompt, send, queue, or none, specifying what action you want taken when an internal compiler error occurs.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid option 'option' for ErrorReport; must be prompt, send, queue, or none - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1630

Rules.Title: Cannot yield a value in the body of a catch clause
Rules.Description: The yield statement is not allowed from within the body of a catch clause. To avoid this error, move the yield statement outside the body of the catch clause.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot yield a value in the body of a catch clause - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1631

Rules.Title: Control cannot leave the body of an anonymous method or lambda expression
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a jump statement (break, goto, continue, etc.) attempts to move control out of an anonymous method block. An anonymous method block is a function body and can only be exited by a return statement or by reaching the end of the block.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Control cannot leave the body of an anonymous method or lambda expression - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1632

Rules.Title: Iterators cannot have unsafe parameters or yield types
Rules.Description: Check the argument list of the iterator and the type of any yield statements to verify that you are not using any unsafe types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Iterators cannot have unsafe parameters or yield types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1637

Rules.Title: 'identifier' is a reserved identifier and cannot be used when ISO language version mode is used
Rules.Description: When the ISO language compatibility option is specified by the /langversion compiler switch, any identifier with double underscores anywhere in the identifier will produce this error. To avoid this error, eliminate any identifiers with double underscores, or do not use the ISO-1 language version option.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'identifier' is a reserved identifier and cannot be used when ISO language version mode is used - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1638

Rules.Title: The managed coclass wrapper class signature 'signature' for interface 'interface' is not a valid class name signature
Rules.Description: This error occurs if the metadata for the interface is invalid. This should never occur if the interface was generated using C# or a supported .NET language. Check with the vendor of the interface or verify that the interface assembly was generated successfully.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The managed coclass wrapper class signature 'signature' for interface 'interface' is not a valid class name signature - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1639

Rules.Title: foreach statement cannot operate on variables of type 'type' because it implements multiple instantiations of 'interface', try casting to a specific interface instantiation
Rules.Description: The type inherits from two or more instances of IEnumerator<T>, which means there is not a unique enumeration of the type that foreach could use. Specify the type of IEnumerator<T> or use another looping construct.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - foreach statement cannot operate on variables of type 'type' because it implements multiple instantiations of 'interface', try casting to a specific interface instantiation - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1640

Rules.Title: A fixed size buffer field must have the array size specifier after the field name
Rules.Description: Unlike regular arrays, fixed size buffers require a constant size to be specified at the declaration point. To resolve this error, add a positive integer literal or a constant positive integer and put the square brackets after the identifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A fixed size buffer field must have the array size specifier after the field name - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1641

Rules.Title: Fixed size buffer fields may only be members of structs.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you use a fixed size buffer field in a class, instead of a struct. To resolve this error, change the class to a struct or declare the field as an ordinary array.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fixed size buffer fields may only be members of structs. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1642

Rules.Title: Not all code paths return a value in method of type 'type!'
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a delegate body does not have a return statement, or has a return statement that the compiler is unable to verify will be reached. In the example below, the compiler does not attempt to predict the result of the branching condition in order to verify that the anonymous method block always returns a value.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Not all code paths return a value in method of type 'type!' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1643

Rules.Title: Feature 'feature' is not part of the standardized ISO C# language specification, and may not be accepted by other compilers
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you specified the LangVersion option ISO-1 and the code you are compiling uses features that are not part of the ISO 1.0 standard. To resolve this error, do not use any of the C# 2.0 compiler features such as generics or anonymous methods with the ISO-1 compatibility option.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Feature 'feature' is not part of the standardized ISO C# language specification, and may not be accepted by other compilers - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1644

Rules.Title: Keyword, identifier, or string expected after verbatim specifier: @
Rules.Description: See string literals for the usage of the verbatim specifier '@'. The verbatim specifier is only allowed before a string, keyword or identifier. To resolve this error, remove the @ symbol from any inappropriate place or add the intended string, keyword or identifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Keyword, identifier, or string expected after verbatim specifier: @ - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1646

Rules.Title: An expression is too long or complex to compile near 'code'
Rules.Description: There was a stack overflow in the compiler processing your code. To resolve this error, simplify your code. If your code is valid, get help at the Developer Community site or StackOverflow.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression is too long or complex to compile near 'code' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1647

Rules.Title: Members of readonly field 'identifier' cannot be modified (except in a constructor or a variable initializer)
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you attempt to modify a member of a field which is readonly where it is not allowed to be modified. To resolve this error, limit assignments to readonly fields to the constructor or variable initializer, or remove the readonly keyword from the declaration of the field.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Members of readonly field 'identifier' cannot be modified (except in a constructor or a variable initializer) - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1648

Rules.Title: Members of readonly field 'identifier' cannot be passed ref or out (except in a constructor)
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you pass a variable to a function that is a member of a readonly field as a ref or out argument. Since ref and out parameters may be modified by the function, this is not allowed. To resolve this error, remove the readonly keyword on the field, or do not pass the members of the readonly field to the function. For example, you might try creating a temporary variable which can be modified and passing the temporary as a ref argument, as shown in the following example.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Members of readonly field 'identifier' cannot be passed ref or out (except in a constructor) - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1649

Rules.Title: Fields of static readonly field 'identifier' cannot be assigned to (except in a static constructor or a variable initializer)
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you attempt to modify a member of a field which is readonly and static where it is not allowed to be modified. To resolve this error, limit assignments to readonly fields to the constructor or variable initializer, or remove the readonly keyword from the declaration of the field.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fields of static readonly field 'identifier' cannot be assigned to (except in a static constructor or a variable initializer) - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1650

Rules.Title: Fields of static readonly field 'identifier' cannot be passed ref or out (except in a static constructor)
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you pass a variable to a function that is a member of a static readonly field as a ref argument. Since ref parameters may be modified by the function, this is not allowed. To resolve this error, remove the readonly keyword on the field, or do not pass the members of the readonly field to the function. For example, you might try creating a temporary variable which can be modified and passing the temporary as a ref argument, as shown in the following example.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fields of static readonly field 'identifier' cannot be passed ref or out (except in a static constructor) - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1651

Rules.Title: Cannot modify members of 'variable' because it is a 'read-only variable type'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you try to modify members of a variable which is read-only because it is in a special construct.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot modify members of 'variable' because it is a 'read-only variable type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1654

Rules.Title: Cannot pass fields of 'variable' as a ref or out argument because it is a 'readonly variable type'
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you are attempting to pass a member of a foreach variable, a using variable, or a fixed variable to a function as a ref or out argument. Because these variables are considered read-only in these contexts, this is not allowed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot pass fields of 'variable' as a ref or out argument because it is a 'readonly variable type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1655

Rules.Title: Cannot assign to 'variable' because it is a 'read-only variable type'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when an assignment to variable occurs in a read-only context. Read-only contexts include foreach iteration variables, using variables, and fixed variables. To resolve this error, avoid assignments to a statement variable in using blocks, foreach statements, and fixed statements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign to 'variable' because it is a 'read-only variable type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1656

Rules.Title: Cannot pass 'parameter' as a ref or out argument because 'reason''
Rules.Description: This error occurs when a variable is passed as a ref or out argument in a context in which that variable is readonly. Readonly contexts include foreach iteration variables, using variables, and fixed variables. To resolve this error, do not call functions that take the foreach, using or fixed variable as a ref or out parameter in using blocks, foreach statements, and fixed statements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot pass 'parameter' as a ref or out argument because 'reason'' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1657

Rules.Title: Cannot convert anonymous method block to type 'type' because it is not a delegate type
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you try to assign or otherwise convert an anonymous method block to a type which is not a delegate type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert anonymous method block to type 'type' because it is not a delegate type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1660

Rules.Title: Cannot convert anonymous method block to delegate type 'delegate type' because the specified block's parameter types do not match the delegate parameter types
Rules.Description: This error occurs if, in an anonymous method definition, the parameter types of the anonymous method do not match the delegate parameter types. Check the number of parameters, the parameter types, and any ref or out parameters and verify an exact match.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert anonymous method block to delegate type 'delegate type' because the specified block's parameter types do not match the delegate parameter types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1661

Rules.Title: Cannot convert anonymous method block to delegate type 'delegate type' because some of the return types in the block are not implicitly convertible to the delegate return type
Rules.Description: This error occurs if the anonymous method block's return statement had a type that was not implicitly convertible to the return type of the delegate.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert anonymous method block to delegate type 'delegate type' because some of the return types in the block are not implicitly convertible to the delegate return type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1662

Rules.Title: Fixed size buffer type must be one of the following: bool, byte, short, int, long, char, sbyte, ushort, uint, ulong, float or double
Rules.Description: A fixed sized buffer may not be any type other than those listed. To avoid this error, use another type or do not use a fixed array.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fixed size buffer type must be one of the following: bool, byte, short, int, long, char, sbyte, ushort, uint, ulong, float or double - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1663

Rules.Title: Fixed size buffer of length 'length' and type 'type' is too big
Rules.Description: The maximum size of a fixed-size buffer (as determined by the length multiplied by the element size) is 2^31 = 268435455.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fixed size buffer of length 'length' and type 'type' is too big - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1664

Rules.Title: Fixed size buffers must have a length greater than zero
Rules.Description: This error occurs if a fixed size buffer is declared with a zero or negative size. The length of a fixed size buffer must be a positive integer.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fixed size buffers must have a length greater than zero - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1665

Rules.Title: You cannot use fixed size buffers contained in unfixed expressions. Try using the fixed statement.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you use the fixed sized buffer in an expression involving a class that is not itself fixed. The runtime is free to move the unfixed class around to optimize memory access, which could lead to errors when using the fixed sized buffer. To avoid this error, use the fixed keyword on the statement.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - You cannot use fixed size buffers contained in unfixed expressions. Try using the fixed statement. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1666

Rules.Title: Attribute 'attribute' is not valid on property or event accessors. It is valid on 'declaration type' declarations only.
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you use an attribute on a property or event accessor, when it should be on the property or event itself. This error could occur with the attributes CLSCompliantAttribute, ConditionalAttribute, and ObsoleteAttribute.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Attribute 'attribute' is not valid on property or event accessors. It is valid on 'declaration type' declarations only. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1667

Rules.Title: params is not valid in this context
Rules.Description: A number of C# features are incompatible with variable argument lists, and do not allow the params keyword, including the following:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - params is not valid in this context - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1670

Rules.Title: A namespace declaration cannot have modifiers or attributes
Rules.Description: Modifiers are not meaningful when applied to a namespace, so they are not allowed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A namespace declaration cannot have modifiers or attributes - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1671

Rules.Title: Invalid option 'option' for /platform; must be anycpu, x86, Itanium or x64
Rules.Description: The options specify the processor type; use one of the forms listed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid option 'option' for /platform; must be anycpu, x86, Itanium or x64 - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1672

Rules.Title: Anonymous methods, lambda expressions, and query expressions inside structs cannot access instance members of 'this'. Consider copying 'this' to a local variable outside the anonymous method, lambda expression or query expression and using the local instead.
Rules.Description: The following sample generates CS1673:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Anonymous methods, lambda expressions, and query expressions inside structs cannot access instance members of 'this'. Consider copying 'this' to a local variable outside the anonymous method, lambda expression or query expression and using the local instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1673

Rules.Title: 'T': type used in a using statement must be implicitly convertible to 'System.IDisposable'
Rules.Description: The using Statement is intended to be used to ensure the disposal of an object at the end of the using block, thus, only types which are disposable may be used in such a statement. For example, value types are not disposable, and type parameters which are not constrained to be classes may not be assumed to be disposable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'T': type used in a using statement must be implicitly convertible to 'System.IDisposable' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1674

Rules.Title: Enums cannot have type parameters
Rules.Description: To resolve this error, remove the type parameter from the enum declaration.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Enums cannot have type parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1675

Rules.Title: Parameter 'number' must be declared with the 'keyword' keyword
Rules.Description: This error occurs when the parameter type modifier in an anonymous method is different from that used in the declaration of the delegate you are casting the method to.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Parameter 'number' must be declared with the 'keyword' keyword - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1676

Rules.Title: Parameter 'number' should not be declared with the 'keyword' keyword
Rules.Description: This error occurs when the parameter type modifier in an anonymous method does not match that used in the declaration of the delegate, to which you are casting the method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Parameter 'number' should not be declared with the 'keyword' keyword - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1677

Rules.Title: Parameter 'number' is declared as type 'type1' but should be 'type2'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when the parameter type in an anonymous method is different from the declaration of the delegate you are casting the method to.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Parameter 'number' is declared as type 'type1' but should be 'type2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1678

Rules.Title: Invalid extern alias for '/reference'; 'identifier' is not a valid identifier
Rules.Description: When using the external assembly alias feature of the /reference option, the text that follows /reference: and that precedes the '=' must be a valid C# identifier or keyword according to the C# Language Specification.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid extern alias for '/reference'; 'identifier' is not a valid identifier - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1679

Rules.Title: Invalid reference alias option: 'alias=' -- missing filename.
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you use the alias feature with the /reference compiler option without specifying a valid file name.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid reference alias option: 'alias=' -- missing filename. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1680

Rules.Title: You cannot redefine the global extern alias
Rules.Description: The global alias is already defined to include all unaliased references and therefore cannot be redefined.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - You cannot redefine the global extern alias - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1681

Rules.Title: Local 'variable' or its members cannot have their address taken and be used inside an anonymous method or lambda expression
Rules.Description: This error is generated when you use a variable, and attempt to take its address, and one of these actions is done inside an anonymous method.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Local 'variable' or its members cannot have their address taken and be used inside an anonymous method or lambda expression - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1686

Rules.Title: Cannot convert anonymous method block without a parameter list to delegate type 'delegate' because it has one or more out parameters
Rules.Description: The compiler allows parameters to be omitted from an anonymous method block in most cases. This error arises when the anonymous method block does not have a parameter list, but the delegate has an out parameter. The compiler does not allow this situation because it would need to ignore the presence of the out parameter, which is unlikely to be the correct behavior.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert anonymous method block without a parameter list to delegate type 'delegate' because it has one or more out parameters - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1688

Rules.Title: Attribute 'Attribute Name' is only valid on methods or attribute classes
Rules.Description: This error only occurs with the ConditionalAttribute attribute. As the message states, this attribute can only be used on methods or attribute classes. For example, trying to apply this attribute to a class will generate this error.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Attribute 'Attribute Name' is only valid on methods or attribute classes - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1689

Rules.Title: An assembly with the same simple name 'name' has already been imported. Try removing one of the references or sign them to enable side-by-side.
Rules.Description: The compiler removes references that have the same path and file name, but it is possible that the same file exists in two places, or that you forgot to change the version number. This error points out that two references have the same assembly identity and thus the compiler has no way of distinguishing between them in metadata. Either remove one of the redundant references, or make the references unique somehow, such as by incrementing the assembly version number.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An assembly with the same simple name 'name' has already been imported. Try removing one of the references or sign them to enable side-by-side. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1703

Rules.Title: An assembly with the same simple name 'Assembly Name' has already been imported. Try removing one of the references or sign them to enable side-by-side.
Rules.Description: This error points out that two references have the same assembly identity because the assemblies in question lack strong names, they were not signed, and thus the compiler has no way of distinguishing between them in metadata. Thus, the run time ignores the version and culture assembly name properties. The user should remove the redundant reference, rename one of the references, or provide a strong name for them.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An assembly with the same simple name 'Assembly Name' has already been imported. Try removing one of the references or sign them to enable side-by-side. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1704

Rules.Title: Assembly 'AssemblyName1' uses 'TypeName' which has a higher version than referenced assembly 'AssemblyName2'
Rules.Description: You are accessing a type that has a higher version number than the version number in a referenced assembly. Typically, this error is caused by the accidental use of two versions of the same assembly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Assembly 'AssemblyName1' uses 'TypeName' which has a higher version than referenced assembly 'AssemblyName2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1705

Rules.Title: Expression cannot contain anonymous methods  or lambda expressions
Rules.Description: You cannot insert an anonymous method inside an expression.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expression cannot contain anonymous methods  or lambda expressions - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1706

Rules.Title: Fixed size buffers can only be accessed through locals or fields
Rules.Description: A new feature in C# 2.0 is the ability to define an in-line array inside of a struct. Such arrays can only be accessed via local variables or fields, and may not be referenced as intermediate values on the left-hand side of an expression. Also, the arrays cannot be accessed by fields that are static or readonly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Fixed size buffers can only be accessed through locals or fields - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1708

Rules.Title: Unexpected error building metadata name for type Typename1—'Reason'
Rules.Description: This error is often caused by an internal compiler error. Making some minor changes to your code, such as shortening the length of the name, and then recompiling, may resolve this error.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unexpected error building metadata name for type Typename1—'Reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1713

Rules.Title: The base class or interface of TypeName1 could not be resolved or is invalid
Rules.Description: You are implementing TypeName1 from a class or interface that either could not be resolved, for example, the compiler was unable to locate it, or is invalid. The solution is to determine which of these two cases it is, and either more correctly specify the location of the type, or fix any compiler errors in the base class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The base class or interface of TypeName1 could not be resolved or is invalid - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1714

Rules.Title: 'Type1': type must be 'Type2' to match overridden member 'MemberName'
Rules.Description: This error is the same as Compiler Error CS0508, except that CS0508 now only applies to methods that have return types, while CS1715 applies to properties and indexers that only have 'types' instead of 'return types'.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Type1': type must be 'Type2' to match overridden member 'MemberName' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1715

Rules.Title: Do not use 'System.Runtime.CompilerServices.FixedBuffer' attribute. Use the 'fixed' field modifier instead.
Rules.Description: This error arises in an unsafe code section that contains a fixed-size array declaration similar to a field declaration. Do not use this attribute. Instead, use the keyword fixed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Do not use 'System.Runtime.CompilerServices.FixedBuffer' attribute. Use the 'fixed' field modifier instead. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1716

Rules.Title: Error reading Win32 resource file 'File Name' -- 'reason'
Rules.Description: An attempt to read the Win32 resource file failed for the reason given in the error, typically something like "file not found" or "access denied." This error is resolved by correcting the problem described by the reason.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Error reading Win32 resource file 'File Name' -- 'reason' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1719

Rules.Title: Class 'class' cannot have multiple base classes: 'class_1' and 'class_2'
Rules.Description: The most common cause of this error message is attempting to use multiple inheritance. A class in C# may only inherit directly from one class. However, a class can implement any number of interfaces.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Class 'class' cannot have multiple base classes: 'class_1' and 'class_2' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1721

Rules.Title: Base class 'class' must come before any interfaces
Rules.Description: When specifying a class to inherit from and interfaces to implement, the class name must be specified first.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Base class 'class' must come before any interfaces - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1722

Rules.Title: Value specified for the argument to 'System.Runtime.InteropServices.DefaultCharSetAttribute' is not valid
Rules.Description: This error is generated by an invalid argument to the DefaultCharSetAttribute class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Value specified for the argument to 'System.Runtime.InteropServices.DefaultCharSetAttribute' is not valid - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1724

Rules.Title: Friend assembly reference 'reference' is invalid. InternalsVisibleTo declarations cannot have a version, culture, public key token, or processor architecture specified.
Rules.Description: You cannot add a version culture in a friend assembly reference. Partial classes should be visible to friend assemblies.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Friend assembly reference 'reference' is invalid. InternalsVisibleTo declarations cannot have a version, culture, public key token, or processor architecture specified. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1725

Rules.Title: Friend assembly reference 'reference' is invalid. Strong-name signed assemblies must specify a public key in their InternalsVisibleTo declarations.
Rules.Description: A strong name signed assembly can only grant friend assembly access, made with the InternalsVisibleToAttribute, to other strongly signed assemblies.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Friend assembly reference 'reference' is invalid. Strong-name signed assemblies must specify a public key in their InternalsVisibleTo declarations. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1726

Rules.Title: Cannot send error report automatically without authorization. Please visit '' to authorize sending error report.
Rules.Description: The Web site listed in the error text explains how to enable automatic error reporting for Visual Studio 2005 command line tools.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot send error report automatically without authorization. Please visit '' to authorize sending error report. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1727

Rules.Title: Cannot bind delegate to 'member' because it is a member of 'type'
Rules.Description: You cannot bind delegates to members of Nullable value types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot bind delegate to 'member' because it is a member of 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1728

Rules.Title: 'type' does not contain a constructor that takes 'number' arguments.
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you either directly or indirectly invoke the constructor of a class but the compiler cannot find any constructors with the same number of parameters. In the following example, the test class has no constructors that take any arguments. It therefore has only a parameterless constructor that takes zero arguments. Because in the second line in which the error is generated, the derived class declares no constructors of its own, the compiler provides a parameterless constructor. That constructor invokes a parameterless constructor in the base class. Because the base class has no such constructor, CS1729 is generated.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type' does not contain a constructor that takes 'number' arguments. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1729

Rules.Title: Assembly and module attributes must precede all other elements defined in a file except using clauses and extern alias declarations.
Rules.Description: An attribute applied at the assembly level cannot appear after any type definitions.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Assembly and module attributes must precede all other elements defined in a file except using clauses and extern alias declarations. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1730

Rules.Title: Cannot convert 'expression' to delegate because some of the return types in the block are not implicitly convertible to the delegate return type.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when a lambda expression or anonymous method has a return type that is not compatible with the delegate's return type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot convert 'expression' to delegate because some of the return types in the block are not implicitly convertible to the delegate return type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1731

Rules.Title: Expected parameter.
Rules.Description: This error is produced when a lambda expression contains a comma following an input parameter but does not specify the following parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expected parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1732

Rules.Title: Expected expression.
Rules.Description: This error is produced whenever the compiler is expecting an expression on the line where the error occurred. In the following example, the trailing comma in the initializer indicates to the compiler that another expression will follow.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expected expression. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1733

Rules.Title: Warning level must be in the range 0-4
Rules.Description: The WarningLevel compiler option can only take one of six possible values (0, 1, 2, 3, or 4). Any other value passed to /warn will result in CS1900.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Warning level must be in the range 0-4 - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1900

Rules.Title: Invalid option 'option' for /debug; must be full or pdbonly
Rules.Description: An invalid option was passed to the DebugType compiler option.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid option 'option' for /debug; must be full or pdbonly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1902

Rules.Title: Invalid option 'option'; Resource visibility must be either 'public' or 'private'
Rules.Description: This error indicates an invalid Resources (Embed Resource File to Output) or LinkResources (Link to .NET Framework Resource) command line option. Check the syntax of the /resource or /linkresource command line option, and make sure that the accessibility modifier used is either public or private.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid option 'option'; Resource visibility must be either 'public' or 'private' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1906

Rules.Title: The type of the argument to the DefaultValue attribute must match the parameter type
Rules.Description: This error is generated when you use the wrong argument for the DefaultValueAttribute attribute value. Use a value that matches the parameter type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type of the argument to the DefaultValue attribute must match the parameter type - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1908

Rules.Title: The DefaultValue attribute is not applicable on parameters of type 'type'
Rules.Description: CS1909 is generated when you use a DefaultValue attribute that is not applicable on the parameter type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The DefaultValue attribute is not applicable on parameters of type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1909

Rules.Title: Argument of type 'type' is not applicable for the DefaultValue attribute
Rules.Description: For parameters whose type is object, the argument of the DefaultParameterValueAttribute must be null, an integral type, a floating point, bool, string, enum, or char. The argument can not be of type Type or any array type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Argument of type 'type' is not applicable for the DefaultValue attribute - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1910

Rules.Title: Duplicate initialization of member 'name'.
Rules.Description: An object initializer can initialize each member only one time.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Duplicate initialization of member 'name'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1912

Rules.Title: Member 'name' cannot be initialized. It is not a field or property.
Rules.Description: Object initializers can only be used to initialize accessible fields or properties.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Member 'name' cannot be initialized. It is not a field or property. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1913

Rules.Title: Static field 'name' cannot be assigned in an object initializer
Rules.Description: Object initializers by definition initialize objects, or instances, of classes. They cannot be used to initialize a static field of a type. No matter how many instances of a class are created, there is only one copy of a static field.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Static field 'name' cannot be assigned in an object initializer - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1914

Rules.Title: Members of read-only field 'name' of type 'struct name' cannot be assigned with an object initializer because it is of a value type.
Rules.Description: Read-only fields that are value types can only be assigned in a constructor.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Members of read-only field 'name' of type 'struct name' cannot be assigned with an object initializer because it is of a value type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1917

Rules.Title: Members of property 'name' of type 'type' cannot be assigned with an object initializer because it is of a value type.
Rules.Description: This error occurs when you try to use an object initializer to initialize the properties of a struct type that is itself a property of the class that is being initialized.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Members of property 'name' of type 'type' cannot be assigned with an object initializer because it is of a value type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1918

Rules.Title: Unsafe type 'type name' cannot be used in object creation.
Rules.Description: The new operator creates objects only on the managed heap. However, you can create objects in unmanaged memory indirectly by using the interoperability capabilities of the language to call native methods that return pointers.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Unsafe type 'type name' cannot be used in object creation. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1919

Rules.Title: Element initializer cannot be empty.
Rules.Description: A collection initializer consists of a sequence of element initializers. The element initializers do not have to be enclosed in braces unless they contain an assignment expression. However, if you do supply braces, they cannot be empty. If the element initializer is an object initializer, the braces may be empty as long as the initializer contains a new object creation expression.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Element initializer cannot be empty. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1920

Rules.Title: The best overloaded method match for 'method' has wrong signature for the initializer element. The initializable Add must be an accessible instance method.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when you try to use a collection initializer with a class that has no public non-static Add method. If the Add method is not accessible because of its protection level (private, protected, internal) then you will get CS0122, so that this error probably means that the method is defined as static.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The best overloaded method match for 'method' has wrong signature for the initializer element. The initializable Add must be an accessible instance method. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1921

Rules.Title: Collection initializer requires its type 'type' to implement System.Collections.IEnumerable.
Rules.Description: In order to use a collection initializer with a type, the type must implement IEnumerable. This error can occur if you accidentally use collection initializer syntax when you meant to use an object initializer.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Collection initializer requires its type 'type' to implement System.Collections.IEnumerable. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1922

Rules.Title: Cannot initialize object of type 'type' with a collection initializer.
Rules.Description: Collection initializers are only allowed for collection classes that meet certain criteria. For more information, see Object and Collection Initializers. This error is also produced when you try to use the short form of an array initializer nested inside a collection initializer.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot initialize object of type 'type' with a collection initializer. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1925

Rules.Title: Error reading Win32 manifest file 'filename' -- 'error'.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when the following conditions are true:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Error reading Win32 manifest file 'filename' -- 'error'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1926

Rules.Title: 'Type' does not contain a definition for 'method' and the best extension method overload 'method' has some invalid arguments.
Rules.Description: This error is produced when the compiler cannot find a class member with the name of the method you have called. It can find an extension method with that name, but not with a signature that matches the types you passed in with your method call.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'Type' does not contain a definition for 'method' and the best extension method overload 'method' has some invalid arguments. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1928

Rules.Title: Instance argument: cannot convert from 'typeA' to 'typeB'.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when you try to invoke an extension method from a class that it does not extend. In the example shown here, the extension method is defined for the derived class A, but not for the base class B.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Instance argument: cannot convert from 'typeA' to 'typeB'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1929

Rules.Title: The range variable 'name' has already been declared
Rules.Description: The range variable in a query expression is in scope until the query expression terminates. It must therefore have a unique identifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The range variable 'name' has already been declared - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1930

Rules.Title: The range variable 'variable' conflicts with a previous declaration of 'variable'.
Rules.Description: The declaration of a range variable, just like every other declaration, must have an identifier which is unique within the variable's declaration space.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The range variable 'variable' conflicts with a previous declaration of 'variable'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1931

Rules.Title: Cannot assign 'expression' to a range variable.
Rules.Description: The compiler must be able to infer the type of a range variable, whether it is introduced in a from clause or a let clause. It cannot be null because null is not a type, and it cannot be assigned with an expression of an unsafe type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot assign 'expression' to a range variable. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1932

Rules.Title: Expression cannot contain query expressions
Rules.Description: Some variables cannot be initialized with a query expression. Constants cannot be initialized with query expressions because constants may only be initialized with some combination of literals, named constants, and mathematical operators.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expression cannot contain query expressions - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1933

Rules.Title: Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'. 'method' not found. Consider explicitly specifying the type of the range variable 'name'.
Rules.Description: This error is produced if a query expression specifies a data source for which no standard query operators are implemented. One way to produce this error is to specify an ArrayList without giving an explicit type for the range variable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'. 'method' not found. Consider explicitly specifying the type of the range variable 'name'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1934

Rules.Title: Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'. 'method' not found. Are you missing a using directive for 'System.Linq'?
Rules.Description: The source type in a query must be IEnumerable, IEnumerable<T>, or a derived type, or a type for which you or someone else has implemented the standard query operators. If the source type is an IEnumerable or IEnumerable<T>, you must add a using directive for the System.Linq namespace in order to bring the standard query operator extension methods into scope. Custom implementations of the standard query operators must be brought into scope in the same way, with a using directive and, if necessary, a reference to the assembly.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'. 'method' not found. Are you missing a using directive for 'System.Linq'? - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1935

Rules.Title: Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'.  'method' not found.
Rules.Description: In order to query a source type, that type must implement the standard query operator methods that you are invoking in the query. The implementation can be either in the form of class members or extension methods that are brought into scope with the appropriate using directive.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Could not find an implementation of the query pattern for source type 'type'.  'method' not found. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1936

Rules.Title: The name 'name' is not in scope on the left side of 'equals'. Consider swapping the expressions on either side of 'equals'.
Rules.Description: The equals keyword is a special operator that is used in a join clause to determine equality between two expressions. The range variable for the left side source sequence is in scope on the left side of equals, and the range variable for the right side source is only in scope on the left side of equals. You can verify this by experimenting with IntelliSense in the following code example.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The name 'name' is not in scope on the left side of 'equals'. Consider swapping the expressions on either side of 'equals'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1937

Rules.Title: The name 'name' is not in scope on the right side of 'equals'. Consider swapping the expressions on either side of 'equals'.
Rules.Description: The equals keyword is a special operator that is used in a join clause to determine equality between two expressions. The range variable for the left side source sequence is in scope on the left side of equals, and the range variable for the right side source is only in scope on the left side of equals. You can verify this by experimenting with IntelliSense in the following code example.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The name 'name' is not in scope on the right side of 'equals'. Consider swapping the expressions on either side of 'equals'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1938

Rules.Title: Cannot pass the range variable 'name' as an out or ref parameter.
Rules.Description: A range variable is a read-only variable that is introduced in a query expression and serves as an identifier for each successive element in a source sequence. Because it cannot be modified in any way, there is no point in passing it by ref or out. Therefore, both operations are not valid.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Cannot pass the range variable 'name' as an out or ref parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1939

Rules.Title: Multiple implementations of the query pattern were found for source type 'type'. Ambiguous call to 'method'.
Rules.Description: This error is generated when multiple implementations of a query method are defined and the compiler cannot disambiguate which one is best to use for the query. In the following example, both versions of Select have the same signature, because they both accept one int as an input parameter and have int as a return value.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Multiple implementations of the query pattern were found for source type 'type'. Ambiguous call to 'method'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1940

Rules.Title: The type of one of the expressions in the 'clause' clause is incorrect. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'.
Rules.Description: Type inference in query expressions flows from the type of the elements in the data source(s).
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type of one of the expressions in the 'clause' clause is incorrect. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1941

Rules.Title: The type of the expression in the 'clause' clause is incorrect. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'.
Rules.Description: This error is typically generated when the range variable has been given an incorrect explicit type.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The type of the expression in the 'clause' clause is incorrect. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1942

Rules.Title: An expression of type 'type' is not allowed in a subsequent from clause in a query expression with source type 'type'. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'.
Rules.Description: All range variables must represent queryable types.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression of type 'type' is not allowed in a subsequent from clause in a query expression with source type 'type'. Type inference failed in the call to 'method'. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1943

Rules.Title: An expression tree may not contain an unsafe pointer operation
Rules.Description: Expression trees do not support pointer types because the Expression<TDelegate>.Compile method is only allowed to produce verifiable code. See comments.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree may not contain an unsafe pointer operation - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1944

Rules.Title: An expression tree may not contain an anonymous method expression.
Rules.Description: Expression trees can only contain expressions. Anonymous methods can only represent statements.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree may not contain an anonymous method expression. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1945

Rules.Title: An anonymous method expression cannot be converted to an expression tree.
Rules.Description: An anonymous method represents a set of statements but an expression tree must not contain a statement. Therefore an anonymous method cannot be represented by an expression tree.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An anonymous method expression cannot be converted to an expression tree. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1946

Rules.Title: Range variable 'variable name' cannot be assigned to -- it is read only.
Rules.Description: A range variable is like an iteration variable in a foreach statement. It cannot be assigned to in a query expression.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Range variable 'variable name' cannot be assigned to -- it is read only. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1947

Rules.Title: The range variable 'name' cannot have the same name as a method type parameter
Rules.Description: The same declaration space cannot contain two declarations of the same identifier.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The range variable 'name' cannot have the same name as a method type parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1948

Rules.Title: The contextual keyword 'var' cannot be used in a range variable declaration.
Rules.Description: A range variable is implicitly typed by the compiler. There is no need to use var with a range variable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The contextual keyword 'var' cannot be used in a range variable declaration. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1949

Rules.Title: The best overloaded Add method 'name' for the collection initializer has some invalid arguments.
Rules.Description: To support collection initializers, a class must implement IEnumerable and have a public Add method. To initialize the type by using a collection initializer, the input parameter of the Add method must be compatible with the type of the object you are trying to add.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The best overloaded Add method 'name' for the collection initializer has some invalid arguments. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1950

Rules.Title: An expression tree lambda may not contain an in, out, or ref parameter.
Rules.Description: An expression tree just represents expressions as data structures. There is no way to represent specific memory locations as is required when you pass a parameter by reference.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree lambda may not contain an in, out, or ref parameter. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1951

Rules.Title: An expression tree lambda may not contain a method with variable arguments
Rules.Description: The unsupported __arglist keyword is not allowed in lambda expressions that compile to expression trees.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree lambda may not contain a method with variable arguments - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1952

Rules.Title: An expression tree lambda may not contain a method group.
Rules.Description: A method call requires the () operator. The method name without that operator refers to the method group, which is the set of all the overloaded methods with that name.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - An expression tree lambda may not contain a method group. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1953

Rules.Title: The best overloaded method match 'method' for the collection initializer element cannot be used. Collection initializer 'Add' methods cannot have ref or out parameters.
Rules.Description: For a collection class to be initialized by using a collection initializer, the class must have a public Add method that is not a ref or out parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The best overloaded method match 'method' for the collection initializer element cannot be used. Collection initializer 'Add' methods cannot have ref or out parameters. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1954

Rules.Title: Non-invocable member 'name' cannot be used like a method.
Rules.Description: Only methods and delegates can be invoked. This error is generated when you try to use empty parentheses to call something other than a method or delegate.

Rules.Title: Object and collection initializer expressions may not be applied to a delegate creation expression,
Rules.Description: A delegate has no members like a class or struct has, and so there is nothing for an object initializer to initialize. If you encounter this error, it is probably because there are braces after the delegate creation expression. Just remove the braces and this error will disappear.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Object and collection initializer expressions may not be applied to a delegate creation expression, - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1958

Rules.Title: 'name' is of type 'type'. The type specified in a constant declaration must be sbyte, byte, short, ushort, int, uint, long, ulong, char, float, double, decimal, bool, string, an enum-type, or a reference-type.

Rules.Title: Passing 'argument' as ref or out or taking its address may cause a runtime exception because it is a field of a marshal-by-reference class
Rules.Description: Any class that derives, directly or indirectly, from MarshalByRefObject is a marshal-by-reference class. Such a class can be marshaled by reference across process and machine boundaries. Thus, instances of this class could be proxies to remote objects. You cannot pass a field of a proxy object as ref or out. So, you cannot pass fields of such a class as ref or out, unless the instance is this, which can not be a proxy object.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Passing 'argument' as ref or out or taking its address may cause a runtime exception because it is a field of a marshal-by-reference class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs0197

Rules.Title: 'identifier': a reference to a volatile field will not be treated as volatile
Rules.Description: A volatile field should not normally be passed using a ref or out parameter, since it will not be treated as volatile within the scope of the function. There are exceptions to this, such as when calling an interlocked API. As with any warning, you may use the #pragma warning to disable this warning in those rare cases where you are intentionally using a volatile field as a reference parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'identifier': a reference to a volatile field will not be treated as volatile - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs0420
