Rules.Title: Reference to type 'type' claims it is nested within 'nested type', but it could not be found
Rules.Description: This error arises when you import references that do not agree with other references or with code you have written. A common way to get this error is to write code that refers to a class in metadata, and then you either delete that class or modify its definition.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Reference to type 'type' claims it is nested within 'nested type', but it could not be found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1682

Rules.Title: Reference to type 'Type Name' claims it is defined in this assembly, but it is not defined in source or any added modules
Rules.Description: This error can occur when you are importing an assembly that contains a reference back to the assembly you are currently compiling, but the assembly being compiled contains nothing matching the reference. One way to get to this situation is to compile your assembly, which initially does contain the member that the assembly being imported is referencing. Then you update your assembly, mistakenly removing the members that the imported assembly is referencing.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Reference to type 'Type Name' claims it is defined in this assembly, but it is not defined in source or any added modules - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1683

Rules.Title: Reference to type 'Type Name' claims it is defined in 'Namespace', but it could not be found
Rules.Description: This error can be caused by a reference inside one namespace referring to a type that it says exists inside a second namespace, but the type does not exist. For example, mydll.dll says that type A exists inside yourdll.dll, but no such type exists inside yourdll.dll. One possible cause of this error is that the version of yourdll.dll you are using is too old and A has not yet been defined.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Reference to type 'Type Name' claims it is defined in 'Namespace', but it could not be found - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1684

Rules.Title: The predefined type 'System.type name' is defined in multiple assemblies in the global alias; using definition from 'File Name'
Rules.Description: This error occurs when a predefined system type such as System.int32 is found in two assemblies. One way this can happen is if you are referencing mscorlib from two different places, such as trying to run the .NET Framework versions 1.0 and 1.1 side-by-side.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - The predefined type 'System.type name' is defined in multiple assemblies in the global alias; using definition from 'File Name' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1685

Rules.Title: Source file has exceeded the limit of 16,707,565 lines representable in the PDB, debug information will be incorrect
Rules.Description: The PDB and debugger have some limitations about how big a file can be. If the source file is too big, the debugger will not behave properly beyond that limit. The user should either not emit debug information for that file by possibly using #line hidden, or they should find a way to shrink the file, possibly by splitting the file into multiple files. They might want to use the partial keyword to split up a large class.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Source file has exceeded the limit of 16,707,565 lines representable in the PDB, debug information will be incorrect - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1687

Rules.Title: Accessing a member on 'member' may cause a runtime exception because it is a field of a marshal-by-reference class
Rules.Description: This warning occurs when you try to call a method, property, or indexer on a member of a class that derives from MarshalByRefObject, and the member is a value type. Objects that inherit from MarshalByRefObject are typically intended to be marshaled by reference across an application domain. If any code ever attempts to directly access the value-type member of such an object across an application domain, a runtime InvalidOperationException will occur. To resolve the warning, first copy the member into a local variable and call the method on that variable.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Accessing a member on 'member' may cause a runtime exception because it is a field of a marshal-by-reference class - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1690

Rules.Title: 'number' is not a valid warning number
Rules.Description: A number that was passed to the #pragma warning preprocessor directive was not a valid warning number. Verify that the number represents a warning, not an error or another sequence of characters.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'number' is not a valid warning number - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1691

Rules.Title: Invalid number
Rules.Description: A number of preprocessor directives, such as #pragma and #line, use numbers as parameters. One of these numbers is invalid because it is too big, in the wrong format, contains illegal characters, and so on. To correct this error, correct the number.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid number - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1692

Rules.Title: Invalid filename specified for preprocessor directive. Filename is too long or not a valid filename.
Rules.Description: This warning occurs when using the #pragma checksum preprocessor directive. The file name specified is longer than 256 characters. To resolve this warning, use a shorter file name.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid filename specified for preprocessor directive. Filename is too long or not a valid filename. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1694

Rules.Title: Invalid #pragma checksum syntax; should be #pragma checksum "filename" "{XXXXXXXX-XXXX-XXXX-XXXX-XXXXXXXXXXXX}" "XXXX..."
Rules.Description: You should rarely encounter this error since the checksum is generally inserted at run time if you are generating code by means of the Code Dom API.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Invalid #pragma checksum syntax; should be #pragma checksum "filename" "{XXXXXXXX-XXXX-XXXX-XXXX-XXXXXXXXXXXX}" "XXXX..." - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1695

Rules.Title: Single-line comment or end-of-line expected
Rules.Description: The compiler requires a preprocessor directive to be followed by an end-of-line terminator or by a single-line comment. The compiler has finished processing a valid preprocessor directive, and has encountered something that violates this syntax constraint.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Single-line comment or end-of-line expected - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1696

Rules.Title: Different checksum values given for 'file name'
Rules.Description: You have specified more than one checksum for a given file. The debugger uses the checksum value to determine which file to debug when there is more than one file in a project with the same name. Most users will not encounter this error, but if you are writing an application that generates code, you may run into it. To resolve this error, ensure that you generate the checksum only once for any given code file.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Different checksum values given for 'file name' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1697

Rules.Title: Use command line option "compiler_option" or appropriate project settings instead of "attribute_name"
Rules.Description: In order to sign an assembly, it is necessary to specify a key file. Prior to C# 2.0, you specified the key file using CLR attributes in source code. These attributes are now deprecated.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Use command line option "compiler_option" or appropriate project settings instead of "attribute_name" - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1699

Rules.Title: Delegate 'DelegateName' bound to 'MethodName1' instead of 'MethodName2' because of new language rules
Rules.Description: C# 2.0 implements new rules for binding a delegate to a method. Additional information is considered that was not looked at in the past. This warning indicates that the delegate is now bound to a different overload of the method than it was previously bound to. You may wish to verify that the delegate really should be bound to 'MethodName1' instead of 'MethodName2'.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Delegate 'DelegateName' bound to 'MethodName1' instead of 'MethodName2' because of new language rules - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1707

Rules.Title: Filename specified for preprocessor directive is empty
Rules.Description: You have specified a preprocessor directive that includes a file name, but that file is empty. To resolve this warning, put the needed content into the file.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Filename specified for preprocessor directive is empty - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1709

Rules.Title: Expression will always cause a System.NullReferenceException because the default value of 'generic type' is null
Rules.Description: If you write an expression involving the default of a generic type variable that is a reference type (for example, a class), this error will occur. Consider the following expression:
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Expression will always cause a System.NullReferenceException because the default value of 'generic type' is null - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1720

Rules.Title: XML comment on 'param' has cref attribute 'attribute' that refers to a type parameter
Rules.Description: This error is generated by an XML comment that refers to a type parameter.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - XML comment on 'param' has cref attribute 'attribute' that refers to a type parameter - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1723

Rules.Title: A reference was created to embedded interop assembly '<assembly1>' because of an indirect reference to that assembly from assembly '<assembly2>'. Consider changing the 'Embed Interop Types' property on either assembly.
Rules.Description: You have added a reference to an assembly (assembly1) that has the Embed Interop Types property set to True. This instructs the compiler to embed interop type information from that assembly. However, the compiler cannot embed interop type information from that assembly because another assembly that you have referenced (assembly2) also references that assembly (assembly1) and has the Embed Interop Types property set to False.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - A reference was created to embedded interop assembly '<assembly1>' because of an indirect reference to that assembly from assembly '<assembly2>'. Consider changing the 'Embed Interop Types' property on either assembly. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1762

Rules.Title: Access to member 'name' through a 'base' keyword from an anonymous method, lambda expression, query expression, or iterator results in unverifiable code. Consider moving the access into a helper method on the containing type.
Rules.Description: Calling virtual functions with the base keyword inside the method body of an iterator or anonymous methods will result in unverifiable code. Unverifiable code will fail to run in a partial trust environment.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Access to member 'name' through a 'base' keyword from an anonymous method, lambda expression, query expression, or iterator results in unverifiable code. Consider moving the access into a helper method on the containing type. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1911

Rules.Title: Member 'name' implements interface member 'name' in type 'type'. There are multiple matches for the interface member at run-time. It is implementation dependent which method will be called.
Rules.Description: This warning can be generated when two interface methods are differentiated only by whether a particular parameter is marked with ref or with out. It is best to change your code to avoid this warning because it is not obvious or guaranteed which method is called at run time.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Member 'name' implements interface member 'name' in type 'type'. There are multiple matches for the interface member at run-time. It is implementation dependent which method will be called. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1956

Rules.Title: Member 'name' overrides 'method'. There are multiple override candidates at run-time. It is implementation dependent which method will be called.
Rules.Description: Method parameters that vary only by whether they are ref or out cannot be differentiated at run-time.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Member 'name' overrides 'method'. There are multiple override candidates at run-time. It is implementation dependent which method will be called. - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs1957

Rules.Title: Source file 'file' specified multiple times
Rules.Description: A source file name was passed to the compiler more than once. You can only specify a file once to the compiler to build an output file.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Source file 'file' specified multiple times - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs2002

Rules.Description: The -noconfig compiler option was specified in a response file, which is not allowed.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Ignoring /noconfig option because it was specified in a response file - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs2023

Rules.Title: Invalid value for '/define'; 'identifier' is not a valid identifier
Rules.Description: This warning occurs if the value that is used in the DefineConstants option has some invalid characters.

Rules.Title: Methods with variable arguments are not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: The arguments used in the method expose features that are not in the Common Language Specifications (CLS). For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Methods with variable arguments are not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3000

Rules.Title: Argument type 'type' is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A public, protected, or protected internal method must accept a parameter whose type is compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS compliance, see  Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Argument type 'type' is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3001

Rules.Title: Return type of 'method' is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A public, protected, or protected internal method must return a value whose type is compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Return type of 'method' is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3002

Rules.Title: Type of 'variable' is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A public, protected, or protected internal variable must be of a type that is compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Type of 'variable' is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs3003

Rules.Title: Mixed and decomposed Unicode characters are not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: Only composed UNICODE characters are allowed in public, protected, or protected internal identifiers in order to be compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Mixed and decomposed Unicode characters are not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3004

Rules.Title: Identifier 'identifier' differing only in case is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A public, protected, or protected internal identifier, which differs from another public, protected, or protected internal identifier only in the case of one or more letters, is not compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Identifier 'identifier' differing only in case is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3005

Rules.Title: Overloaded method 'method' differing only in ref or out, or in array rank, is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A method does not cannot be overloaded based on the ref or out parameter and still comply with the Common Language Specification (CLS). For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Overloaded method 'method' differing only in ref or out, or in array rank, is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3006

Rules.Title: Overloaded method 'method' differing only by unnamed array types is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: This error occurs if you have an overloaded method that takes a jagged array and the only difference between the method signatures is the element type of the array. To avoid this error, consider using a rectangular array rather than a jagged array; use an additional parameter to disambiguate the function call; rename one or more of the overloaded methods; or, if CLS Compliance is not needed, remove the CLSCompliantAttribute attribute. For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Overloaded method 'method' differing only by unnamed array types is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs3007

Rules.Title: Identifier 'identifier' differing only in case is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A public, protected, or protected internal identifier breaks compliance with the Common Language Specification (CLS) if it begins with an underscore character (_). For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Identifier 'identifier' differing only in case is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3008

Rules.Title: 'type': base type 'type' is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: A base type was marked as not having to be compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS) in an assembly that was marked as being CLS compliant. Either remove the attribute that specifies the assembly is CLS compliant or remove the attribute that indicates the type is not CLS compliant. For more information on CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type': base type 'type' is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs3009

Rules.Title: 'member': CLS-compliant interfaces must have only CLS-compliant members
Rules.Description: In an assembly marked with [assembly:CLSCompliant(true)], an interface contains a member marked with [CLSCompliant(false)]. Remove one of the Common Language Specification (CLS) compliance attributes. For more information about CLS Compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member': CLS-compliant interfaces must have only CLS-compliant members - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3010

Rules.Title: 'member': only CLS-compliant members can be abstract
Rules.Description: A class member cannot be both abstract and non-compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS). The CLS specifies that all class members shall be implemented. For more information about CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member': only CLS-compliant members can be abstract - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3011

Rules.Title: You cannot specify the CLSCompliant attribute on a module that differs from the CLSCompliant attribute on the assembly
Rules.Description: In order for a module to be compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS) through [module:System.CLSCompliant(true)], it must be built with the module element of the TargetType compiler option. For more information on the CLS, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - You cannot specify the CLSCompliant attribute on a module that differs from the CLSCompliant attribute on the assembly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3012

Rules.Title: Added modules must be marked with the CLSCompliant attribute to match the assembly

Rules.TitleAndLink: - Added modules must be marked with the CLSCompliant attribute to match the assembly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3013

Rules.Title: 'member' does not need a CLSCompliant attribute because the assembly does not have a CLSCompliant attribute
Rules.Description: In a source code file where compliance with the Common Language Specification (CLS) was not specified, a construct in the file was marked as being CLS compliant. This is not allowed. To resolve this warning, add an assembly level CLS compliant attribute to the file (in the following example, uncomment the line that contains the assembly level attribute). For more information about CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'member' does not need a CLSCompliant attribute because the assembly does not have a CLSCompliant attribute - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3014

Rules.Title: 'method signature' has no accessible constructors which use only CLS-compliant types
Rules.Description: To be compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS), the argument list of an attribute class cannot contain an array. For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'method signature' has no accessible constructors which use only CLS-compliant types - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3015

Rules.Title: Arrays as attribute arguments is not CLS-compliant
Rules.Description: It is not compliant with the Common Language Specification (CLS) to pass an array to an attribute. For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - Arrays as attribute arguments is not CLS-compliant - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3016

Rules.Title: You cannot specify the CLSCompliant attribute on a module that differs from the CLSCompliant attribute on the assembly
Rules.Description: This warning occurs if you have a assembly CLSCompliant attribute that conflicts with a module CLSCompliant attribute. An assembly that is CLS compliant cannot contain modules that are not CLS compliant. To resolve this warning, make sure the assembly and module CLSCompliant attributes are either both true or both false, or remove one of the attributes. For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - You cannot specify the CLSCompliant attribute on a module that differs from the CLSCompliant attribute on the assembly - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3017

Rules.Title: 'type' cannot be marked as CLS-Compliant because it is a member of non CLS-compliant type 'type'
Rules.Description: This warning occurs if a nested class with the CLSCompliant attribute set to true is declared as a member of a class declared with the CLSCompliant attribute set to false. This is not allowed, since a nested class cannot be CLS-compliant if it is a member of an outer class that is not CLS-compliant. To resolve this warning, remove the CLSCompliant attribute from the nested class, or change it from true to false. For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
Rules.TitleAndLink: - 'type' cannot be marked as CLS-Compliant because it is a member of non CLS-compliant type 'type' - https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/misc/cs3018

Rules.Title: CLSCompliant attribute has no meaning when applied to parameters. Try putting it on the method instead.

Rules.Title: Because this call is not awaited, execution of the current method continues before the call is completed. Consider applying the await operator to the result of the call.
Rules.Description: The current method calls an async method that returns a Task or a Task<TResult> and doesn't apply the await operator to the result. The call to the async method starts an asynchronous task. However, because no await operator is applied, the program continues without waiting for the task to complete. In most cases, that behavior isn't what you expect. Usually other aspects of the calling method depend on the results of the call or, minimally, the called method is expected to complete before you return from the method that contains the call.

This warning occurs when the compiler cannot match one of these statements to its pattern due to a method's incorrect signature. For example, the "collection" pattern requires that there be a method called MoveNext which takes no parameters and returns a boolean. Your code might contain a MoveNext method that has a parameter or perhaps returns an object.

Since the assembly is not declaring itself CLS compliant, there is no need for anything within the assembly to declare itself non-compliant, since it is assumed to be non-compliant. For more information on CLS compliance, see Language independence and language-independent components.
